6
00:01:23.960 --> 00:01:25.085
(GASPS)

7
00:01:33.386 --> 00:01:34.761
- (GUN CLICKING)
- (CONTINUES PANTING)

8
00:01:41.811 --> 00:01:43.478
(BOTH PANTING)

9
00:01:43.688 --> 00:01:44.854
(GUN CLICKING)

10
00:01:50.027 --> 00:01:52.028
(GRUNTING)

11
00:02:02.957 --> 00:02:04.207
(GASPS)

12
00:02:08.129 --> 00:02:09.629
(PANTING)

13
00:02:22.018 --> 00:02:23.518
(BOTH GRUNTING)

14
00:02:28.774 --> 00:02:30.066
(YELLING)

15
00:02:42.455 --> 00:02:43.621
(GULPS)

16
00:02:53.507 --> 00:02:54.674
(BOTH GASP)

17
00:03:06.771 --> 00:03:09.564
(KONG ROARING)

18
00:03:17.948 --> 00:03:20.533
HARRY S. TRUMAN: If we can put
this tremendous machine of ours.

19
00:03:20.868 --> 00:03:23.119
which has made this victory possible.

20
00:03:23.662 --> 00:03:24.871
to work for peace.

21
00:03:25.706 --> 00:03:28.500
we can look forward to the greatest age
in the history of mankind.

22
00:03:38.427 --> 00:03:40.512
Speed of progress in the satellite project

23
00:03:41.222 --> 00:03:44.307
cannot be taken as an index
of our progress

24
00:03:44.475 --> 00:03:45.809
in ballistic missile work.

25
00:03:49.355 --> 00:03:51.815
I feel we're on the brink of
an area of expansion

26
00:03:51.982 --> 00:03:54.317
of knowledge about ourselves
and our surroundings

27
00:03:54.485 --> 00:03:57.529
that is beyond description
or comprehension at this time.

28
00:04:01.325 --> 00:04:04.077
MALE NEWSCASTER: For the first time.
we're putting cameras into space

29
00:04:04.245 --> 00:04:06.496
and looking down on the Earth.

30
00:04:06.664 --> 00:04:10.417
allowing us to discover
places and things we've never seen.

31
00:04:13.003 --> 00:04:16.005
MAN: The most intelligent inhabitants
of that future world

32
00:04:16.382 --> 00:04:18.341
won't be men or monkeys.

33
00:04:18.509 --> 00:04:19.676
They'll be machines.

34
00:04:21.262 --> 00:04:23.847
We set sail on this new sea

35
00:04:24.765 --> 00:04:27.267
because there is new knowledge
to be gained.

36
00:04:27.435 --> 00:04:28.685
Whether this new ocean

37
00:04:29.562 --> 00:04:31.354
will be a sea of peace

38
00:04:31.522 --> 00:04:34.774
or a new terrifying theater of war...

39
00:04:37.361 --> 00:04:39.237
"To tame the savageness of man

40
00:04:40.072 --> 00:04:42.365
"and make gentle the life of this world."

41
00:04:43.576 --> 00:04:45.410
Let us dedicate ourselves to that.

42
00:04:52.501 --> 00:04:55.753
(PROTESTORS SHOUTING)

43
00:04:58.257 --> 00:05:00.592
PROTESTORS: (CHANTING)
Stop the war! Stop the war!

44
00:05:00.759 --> 00:05:04.471
- Stop the war!
- MALE NEWSCASTER: As citywide protests

45
00:05:04.638 --> 00:05:07.432
have brought congressional committee
hearings to a standstill.

46
00:05:07.600 --> 00:05:10.393
promising more gridlock
in the days and weeks ahead.

47
00:05:10.561 --> 00:05:12.145
The Beltway is experiencing
significant delays.

48
00:05:12.313 --> 00:05:13.771
Mark my words.

49
00:05:13.939 --> 00:05:16.774
There'll never be a more screwed up time
in Washington.

50
00:05:17.485 --> 00:05:19.569
But we can't let it stop us.

51
00:05:22.448 --> 00:05:24.115
Come on already. let's go!

52
00:05:25.576 --> 00:05:26.910
Get out of the way!

53
00:05:27.077 --> 00:05:28.578
Maybe now's not the best time to ask.

54
00:05:28.746 --> 00:05:32.248
Monarch is on the cusp
of being shut down. Brooks. We're broke!

55
00:05:32.416 --> 00:05:35.793
When this war ends. we'll never
get approval for our expedition.

56
00:05:36.587 --> 00:05:37.754
(BEEPING)

57
00:05:39.173 --> 00:05:41.299
I'm not confident in our presentation.

58
00:05:41.467 --> 00:05:43.510
All of our materials are loose leaf.

59
00:05:43.677 --> 00:05:45.595
In one day. one day.

60
00:05:45.763 --> 00:05:47.597
I could have had all of this
organized and bound.

61
00:05:47.765 --> 00:05:51.267
...that we. today.
have concluded an agreement

62
00:05:51.435 --> 00:05:55.104
to end the war.
and bring peace with honor in Vietnam.

63
00:05:55.272 --> 00:05:57.774
All American forces will be withdrawn.

64
00:05:57.942 --> 00:05:59.275
We don't have a day.

65
00:05:59.443 --> 00:06:00.527
Hello. there.

66
00:06:01.153 --> 00:06:02.487
Bill Randa here to see Senator Willis.

67
00:06:03.280 --> 00:06:04.864
Of course. Mr. Randa.

68
00:06:05.032 --> 00:06:08.368
I left you a message this morning
about rescheduling today's appointment.

69
00:06:09.161 --> 00:06:12.413
But he should have something available
in the coming weeks.

70
00:06:12.581 --> 00:06:13.581
(DOOR OPENS)

71
00:06:14.959 --> 00:06:15.959
Oh. God.

72
00:06:16.126 --> 00:06:17.335
Al. you're looking well.

73
00:06:17.503 --> 00:06:19.379
WILLIS: So you didn't
get the message. Randa?

74
00:06:19.547 --> 00:06:22.048
- To reschedule?
- For the fifth time? I must've missed it.

75
00:06:22.216 --> 00:06:23.800
It'll be quick.

76
00:06:24.468 --> 00:06:26.469
Okay. don't get comfortable.
You got five minutes.

77
00:06:26.679 --> 00:06:27.720
I'm late for a meeting.

78
00:06:28.847 --> 00:06:30.974
So. what imaginary monster
are you hunting this time?

79
00:06:31.141 --> 00:06:33.142
This is a satellite photo

80
00:06:33.310 --> 00:06:35.478
of an uncharted island
in the South Pacific.

81
00:06:35.646 --> 00:06:39.065
It has defied discovery until now.

82
00:06:39.733 --> 00:06:42.360
Many civilizations spoke of it in legends.

83
00:06:43.487 --> 00:06:45.196
Skull Island.

84
00:06:45.364 --> 00:06:48.324
The land where God
did not finish creation.

85
00:06:48.492 --> 00:06:50.201
It's notorious

86
00:06:50.369 --> 00:06:52.704
for the number of ships and planes
that have gone missing there.

87
00:06:53.664 --> 00:06:55.206
Like the Bermuda Triangle?

88
00:06:57.501 --> 00:07:00.837
Or like that aluminum foil hat
that I like to wear on the weekends?

89
00:07:01.005 --> 00:07:03.256
It's more like the triangle than the hat.

90
00:07:03.424 --> 00:07:05.842
but we like to think
it's much more than that.

91
00:07:06.969 --> 00:07:09.178
The 1954 Castle Bravo nuclear tests

92
00:07:09.346 --> 00:07:11.014
weren't tests.

93
00:07:11.181 --> 00:07:12.599
They were trying to kill something.

94
00:07:13.267 --> 00:07:18.021
I believe there's an ecosystem out there
the likes of which we can't imagine.

95
00:07:18.188 --> 00:07:21.357
And the place to find it is this island.

96
00:07:21.525 --> 00:07:24.694
A place where myth and science meet.

97
00:07:24.862 --> 00:07:27.363
Randa. it's a fairy tale.

98
00:07:29.617 --> 00:07:30.617
(DOOR OPENS)

99
00:07:32.077 --> 00:07:35.747
Harry Truman didn't think so
when he funded Monarch in 1946.

100
00:07:35.914 --> 00:07:37.540
In terms of sheer waste.

101
00:07:37.708 --> 00:07:40.585
Monarch ranks right up there
with the search for alien life.

102
00:07:40.753 --> 00:07:42.712
Yeah. but those guys are nuts.

103
00:07:44.465 --> 00:07:46.132
WILLIS: We should have
shut you down years ago.

104
00:07:46.300 --> 00:07:48.384
This is an opportunity for our country.

105
00:07:48.552 --> 00:07:51.888
BROOKS: Listen. Senator. Landsat
is sending a mission to the island.

106
00:07:52.056 --> 00:07:54.307
We could piggyback on that operation.

107
00:07:54.475 --> 00:07:56.225
With your permission. of course.

108
00:07:56.393 --> 00:07:57.602
What're you hoping you'll find?

109
00:07:57.770 --> 00:08:01.731
Resources. medicine. the cure for cancer.
geological discoveries.

110
00:08:02.608 --> 00:08:04.651
Possible alternate fuels.
Senator. look just...

111
00:08:05.486 --> 00:08:06.903
Listen. to be honest.

112
00:08:07.071 --> 00:08:08.571
we don't know for sure what's there.

113
00:08:08.739 --> 00:08:11.074
Okay? But I will tell you what we do know.

114
00:08:11.241 --> 00:08:13.993
Tomorrow night. the Russian Novosat
passes over this sector.

115
00:08:14.161 --> 00:08:16.454
And in three days. they're gonna have
the same images we have.

116
00:08:17.581 --> 00:08:18.998
So whatever's there.

117
00:08:19.625 --> 00:08:22.627
you want us to find it first.

118
00:08:23.671 --> 00:08:24.671
Right?

119
00:08:27.257 --> 00:08:31.427
I don't believe I'm saying this.
but that almost made sense.

120
00:08:32.137 --> 00:08:33.471
- Thank you.
- (WILLIS SIGHS)

121
00:08:33.681 --> 00:08:36.140
So. I will get the piggyback for you.
I will.

122
00:08:36.308 --> 00:08:38.601
But listen to me. listen to me.
This is it.

123
00:08:38.769 --> 00:08:40.311
It's gotta end. This is it.

124
00:08:40.479 --> 00:08:43.606
You promise me? Last favor? Okay?

125
00:08:45.109 --> 00:08:46.109
Senator?

126
00:08:46.527 --> 00:08:47.694
(WILLIS SIGHS)

127
00:08:47.986 --> 00:08:49.195
One last thing.

128
00:08:51.448 --> 00:08:53.616
I'm going to need a military escort.

129
00:08:55.202 --> 00:08:57.745
- (ROCK MUSIC PLAYING)
- (INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

130
00:09:05.838 --> 00:09:07.922
(SOLDIERS CHANTING)

131
00:09:12.469 --> 00:09:15.304
MAN: (ON PA) Attention.
all soldiers and base personnel.

132
00:09:16.056 --> 00:09:19.142
Final troop withdrawal will commence
at 0600.

133
00:09:20.477 --> 00:09:22.478
Pack your bags. ladies.

134
00:09:22.646 --> 00:09:24.355
We're going home.

135
00:09:24.523 --> 00:09:25.523
- RELES: Hey. Mills.
- Yeah?

136
00:09:25.691 --> 00:09:26.816
How many letters
did you end up writing her?

137
00:09:28.402 --> 00:09:29.402
Ten. fifteen.

138
00:09:29.570 --> 00:09:30.570
How many did she write you?

139
00:09:30.738 --> 00:09:31.821
I don't know. three. four.

140
00:09:31.989 --> 00:09:33.114
(WINCING)

141
00:09:33.532 --> 00:09:34.991
Man. you got a shitty mom.

142
00:09:35.325 --> 00:09:36.492
(ALL LAUGHING)

143
00:09:36.702 --> 00:09:38.870
Thank you. Cole. for clearing that up.
Thank you.

144
00:09:39.496 --> 00:09:41.330
I'll be sure to tell her
when I see her in the next 48 hours.

145
00:09:41.498 --> 00:09:42.665
SLIVKO: Yeah. you might have a shitty mom.

146
00:09:42.916 --> 00:09:44.834
- (ALL LAUGHING)
- Right?

147
00:09:45.294 --> 00:09:47.670
(SOLDIERS CONTINUE LAUGHING)

148
00:09:56.513 --> 00:09:59.390
MALE NEWSCASTER: The United States
is making it clear to the Communists

149
00:09:59.558 --> 00:10:03.770
that American troop withdrawal is directly
on the release of U.S. prisoners of war.

150
00:10:03.937 --> 00:10:05.521
Washington notified the Viet Cong

151
00:10:05.689 --> 00:10:07.690
and North Vietnamese today
that the withdrawal...

152
00:10:09.193 --> 00:10:10.193
CHAPMAN: Sir?

153
00:10:10.736 --> 00:10:11.861
Chapman.

154
00:10:13.697 --> 00:10:14.781
You need anything. sir?

155
00:10:15.699 --> 00:10:16.699
All good.

156
00:10:17.284 --> 00:10:18.284
Roger that.

157
00:10:20.704 --> 00:10:23.122
So what're you gonna do
when you get back to the world. Chapman?

158
00:10:23.290 --> 00:10:26.209
Oh. I'm already set up
with Eastern Air Lines.

159
00:10:26.794 --> 00:10:29.212
Grace and Billy all moved in in Atlanta.

160
00:10:30.297 --> 00:10:31.464
just waiting on me.

161
00:10:31.965 --> 00:10:33.049
What about you. sir?

162
00:10:34.968 --> 00:10:36.427
PACKARD: All this for what?

163
00:10:36.595 --> 00:10:37.595
CHAPMAN: Sir?

164
00:10:40.599 --> 00:10:42.892
Get out of here. Chapman.
Go have some fun.

165
00:10:44.061 --> 00:10:45.561
Is everything okay?

166
00:10:47.314 --> 00:10:48.648
Tip-top.

167
00:10:56.907 --> 00:10:59.033
- (INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)
- (SOLDIERS LAUGHING)

168
00:11:02.120 --> 00:11:05.623
Colonel Packard!
There's a phone call for you.

169
00:11:09.086 --> 00:11:10.127
This is Packard.

170
00:11:10.295 --> 00:11:11.754
Packard. it's General Ward.

171
00:11:11.922 --> 00:11:14.090
You and your boys up for one last op?

172
00:11:14.258 --> 00:11:16.008
I would not be opposed to that. sir.

173
00:11:16.176 --> 00:11:18.344
Your orders to head home
are already processed.

174
00:11:18.512 --> 00:11:20.096
Sure you don't wanna take some time?

175
00:11:20.264 --> 00:11:22.640
I'm here to execute
whatever orders I'm given. sir.

176
00:11:22.808 --> 00:11:24.100
Ah. don't get too excited.

177
00:11:24.268 --> 00:11:26.102
Bunch of scientists called Landsat

178
00:11:26.270 --> 00:11:28.145
discovered a new island
on their satellite.

179
00:11:28.313 --> 00:11:31.607
They need helicopter transport
for a survey job.

180
00:11:31.775 --> 00:11:33.776
Roger that. And. sir?

181
00:11:33.944 --> 00:11:34.944
Yes?

182
00:11:35.445 --> 00:11:36.529
Thank you.

183
00:11:41.869 --> 00:11:43.452
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

184
00:11:45.789 --> 00:11:48.291
BROOKS: Randa. I don't get it.
You already got us a military escort.

185
00:11:48.458 --> 00:11:51.127
Why do we need a tracker? And why SAS?

186
00:11:51.295 --> 00:11:53.838
RANDA: Former SAS.
No allegiance to anyone.

187
00:11:54.006 --> 00:11:57.049
And he rescued 12 downed pilots
in –‡ Nang. in '72.

188
00:11:57.217 --> 00:11:59.552
BROOKS: But your source says that
he spends most of his waking hours

189
00:11:59.720 --> 00:12:01.304
in some back alley watering hole.

190
00:12:01.471 --> 00:12:04.390
Is your Yale degree supposed to
lead us through the jungle. Brooks?

191
00:12:04.558 --> 00:12:07.393
Besides. my father told me
never to judge a man by where he drinks.

192
00:12:07.561 --> 00:12:09.145
only how he holds it.

193
00:12:09.313 --> 00:12:11.147
You on board with me here?

194
00:12:11.315 --> 00:12:13.482
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

195
00:12:14.401 --> 00:12:15.401
You go.

196
00:12:20.574 --> 00:12:22.533
BROOKS: Well. Okay.

197
00:12:23.368 --> 00:12:25.828
So. uh. how much do we tell him?

198
00:12:25.996 --> 00:12:28.164
RANDA: Just enough to get him to say yes.

199
00:12:29.041 --> 00:12:31.042
(SLOW MUSIC PLAYING)

200
00:12:46.308 --> 00:12:49.185
(SPEAKING VIETNAMESE)

201
00:12:52.522 --> 00:12:53.648
(GRUNTING)

202
00:12:59.112 --> 00:13:00.154
(EXHALES)

203
00:13:01.031 --> 00:13:03.366
Now there's a man worth talking to.

204
00:13:04.368 --> 00:13:06.077
CONRAD: An uncharted island?

205
00:13:06.578 --> 00:13:08.746
Let me list all the ways you're gonna die.

206
00:13:08.914 --> 00:13:12.583
Rain. heat. mud.
disease carrying flies and mosquitos.

207
00:13:12.751 --> 00:13:15.294
Sure. you could load up on the atabrine
for the malaria.

208
00:13:15.462 --> 00:13:16.879
but what about the other bacteria?

209
00:13:17.047 --> 00:13:20.925
We haven't even started on the things
that want to eat you alive.

210
00:13:21.093 --> 00:13:22.093
We'll double that.

211
00:13:22.260 --> 00:13:25.054
You have no idea how dangerous this is.

212
00:13:25.222 --> 00:13:26.722
I want five times that.

213
00:13:27.641 --> 00:13:29.934
Plus. a bonus if we make it back.

214
00:13:30.102 --> 00:13:31.143
If?

215
00:13:33.563 --> 00:13:34.563
Pay him.

216
00:13:36.733 --> 00:13:39.402
I think Mr. Conrad should be
fairly compensated.

217
00:13:40.779 --> 00:13:42.738
Here's to profit during peacetime.

218
00:13:42.906 --> 00:13:43.906
CONRAD: One question.

219
00:13:44.908 --> 00:13:46.909
You came here looking for a tracker.

220
00:13:47.744 --> 00:13:50.496
Who or what am I tracking?

221
00:13:50.664 --> 00:13:53.082
This is all the information that we have.

222
00:13:53.250 --> 00:13:54.500
Okay? There is no map.

223
00:13:54.668 --> 00:13:56.335
Only satellite images.

224
00:13:56.503 --> 00:13:57.920
So we need someone like you.

225
00:13:58.088 --> 00:14:01.757
with your skill. your unique expertise
in uncharted jungle terrain.

226
00:14:01.925 --> 00:14:03.926
to lead us on our ground expedition.

227
00:14:04.094 --> 00:14:07.596
We're just scholars and scientists.
We need someone with experience.

228
00:14:08.348 --> 00:14:10.558
In case things go sideways.

229
00:14:11.351 --> 00:14:14.186
Men go to war in search of something.
Mr. Conrad.

230
00:14:15.814 --> 00:14:17.773
If you'd found it.

231
00:14:17.941 --> 00:14:19.650
you'd be home by now.

232
00:14:22.571 --> 00:14:24.613
(ROCK MUSIC PLAYING)

233
00:14:38.211 --> 00:14:39.795
(PHONE RINGING)

234
00:14:41.048 --> 00:14:42.465
- Weaver.
- Yeah. it's Jerry.

235
00:14:42.632 --> 00:14:43.716
Hey. Jerry.

236
00:14:43.884 --> 00:14:45.176
So. tell me. did I get it?

237
00:14:45.343 --> 00:14:46.886
That Landsat thing? You got it.

238
00:14:47.054 --> 00:14:48.721
I did? (LAUGHS)

239
00:14:49.514 --> 00:14:50.514
Hello?

240
00:14:50.682 --> 00:14:52.308
It's the Athena. docked in Bangkok.

241
00:14:52.476 --> 00:14:55.311
Pier 14. 6:00 tomorrow night.

242
00:14:55.479 --> 00:14:56.979
1800 tomorrow.

243
00:14:57.981 --> 00:14:59.482
Thank you. I really owe you one.

244
00:14:59.649 --> 00:15:02.318
I don't get it. Why do you want a gig
documenting a mapping mission

245
00:15:02.486 --> 00:15:03.861
when you're up for the cover of Time?

246
00:15:04.029 --> 00:15:07.239
Jerry. when three sources tell you
the same thing word for word.

247
00:15:07.407 --> 00:15:09.158
you know they're lying.

248
00:15:09.826 --> 00:15:13.496
There's something going on here.
something that nobody is talking about.

249
00:15:13.955 --> 00:15:16.457
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

250
00:15:34.726 --> 00:15:36.894
MILLS: I can't believe we're doing this.
Are you guys kidding me?

251
00:15:37.062 --> 00:15:38.229
A day away.

252
00:15:39.022 --> 00:15:40.689
One day away!

253
00:15:40.857 --> 00:15:43.526
And no. now we gotta go to another island

254
00:15:43.693 --> 00:15:45.236
with another jungle.

255
00:15:45.403 --> 00:15:47.738
Vietnam's not an island. dumbass.

256
00:15:47.906 --> 00:15:49.365
Key West is.

257
00:15:49.533 --> 00:15:52.743
and that's exactly where I need to be
right now. with a drink in my hand.

258
00:15:52.911 --> 00:15:55.871
Key West ain't an island either.
it's a key.

259
00:15:58.542 --> 00:16:00.126
You ain't funny. Cole.

260
00:16:00.293 --> 00:16:02.628
(PEOPLE SHOUTING)

261
00:16:11.930 --> 00:16:14.056
Mason Weaver. photographer.

262
00:16:14.224 --> 00:16:17.101
Mason Weaver is a woman?

263
00:16:17.769 --> 00:16:19.478
Last time I checked.

264
00:16:23.316 --> 00:16:24.567
Can I help you?

265
00:16:28.613 --> 00:16:31.073
Two years in country. Where you been?

266
00:16:31.241 --> 00:16:32.950
Embedded with MACV-SOG.

267
00:16:33.160 --> 00:16:34.910
(CHUCKLES)
Ah. you were in the shit.

268
00:16:35.078 --> 00:16:36.579
I respect that.

269
00:16:36.746 --> 00:16:40.291
But it's people like you
lost us support back home.

270
00:16:40.458 --> 00:16:42.835
You're not actually gonna blame
the people without guns

271
00:16:43.003 --> 00:16:44.420
for losing the war. are you?

272
00:16:44.588 --> 00:16:47.006
Camera's way more dangerous than a gun.

273
00:16:47.174 --> 00:16:48.841
And we didn't lose the war.

274
00:16:49.009 --> 00:16:50.426
we abandoned it.

275
00:16:50.927 --> 00:16:53.012
Right. (SCOFFS)

276
00:16:59.394 --> 00:17:00.436
NIEVES: Hello and welcome.

277
00:17:01.271 --> 00:17:04.315
I'm Landsat Field Supervisor.
Victor Nieves.

278
00:17:05.650 --> 00:17:07.109
This is my colleague Steve Woodward.
our data wrangler.

279
00:17:07.360 --> 00:17:08.360
(ALL CHUCKLING)

280
00:17:08.570 --> 00:17:10.321
Our expedition takes us to a place

281
00:17:10.488 --> 00:17:14.450
every nautical trade route known to man
has avoided for centuries.

282
00:17:14.618 --> 00:17:16.619
As our satellites show.

283
00:17:16.786 --> 00:17:19.955
the island is surrounded
by a perpetual storm system.

284
00:17:20.123 --> 00:17:23.500
allowing it to remain hidden
from the outside world.

285
00:17:23.668 --> 00:17:26.420
But with
Colonel Packard's helicopter transport.

286
00:17:26.588 --> 00:17:29.465
we will be the first to break through
to the other side.

287
00:17:30.467 --> 00:17:32.718
We're also pleased to be joined.
for the first time.

288
00:17:32.969 --> 00:17:35.137
by the resource exploration team.

289
00:17:35.305 --> 00:17:36.513
led by Mr. Randa

290
00:17:36.681 --> 00:17:39.099
and accompanied by biologist. Miss San.

291
00:17:39.267 --> 00:17:40.976
and geologist. Mr. Brooks.

292
00:17:41.519 --> 00:17:43.479
Our focus will be on the island's surface.

293
00:17:43.647 --> 00:17:46.023
theirs. what lies beneath.

294
00:17:46.191 --> 00:17:47.191
Mr. Brooks.

295
00:17:47.359 --> 00:17:48.692
Simple. really.

296
00:17:48.860 --> 00:17:51.445
We'll use explosives to shake the earth
and create vibrations.

297
00:17:51.613 --> 00:17:54.323
helping us to map the subsurface
of the island.

298
00:17:54.491 --> 00:17:57.493
We'll fly in over the south shore and
then strategically drop seismic charges

299
00:17:57.661 --> 00:17:59.995
to better help us understand
the density of the earth.

300
00:18:00.163 --> 00:18:01.163
You're dropping bombs?

301
00:18:02.832 --> 00:18:04.208
Mmm... Scientific instruments.

302
00:18:04.376 --> 00:18:05.501
SLIVKO: You hear that. boys?

303
00:18:05.669 --> 00:18:07.294
We're scientists now!

304
00:18:07.504 --> 00:18:08.671
(SOLDIERS LAUGHING)

305
00:18:08.880 --> 00:18:10.381
You guys are not scientists.

306
00:18:11.132 --> 00:18:12.508
NIEVES: We'll then land and make base camp

307
00:18:12.676 --> 00:18:15.302
for ground excursions led by Mr. Conrad.

308
00:18:15.470 --> 00:18:16.512
Major Jack Chapman.

309
00:18:16.680 --> 00:18:18.722
All right. Once on the island.

310
00:18:18.890 --> 00:18:21.517
the storm's interference will block
all radio contact with the ship.

311
00:18:21.685 --> 00:18:23.519
That means we'll be by ourselves.

312
00:18:24.187 --> 00:18:25.187
Three days later. the refuel team

313
00:18:25.355 --> 00:18:26.563
will meet us here
on the north end of the island.

314
00:18:28.066 --> 00:18:31.402
That may be our only safe departure window
for an unknown period of time.

315
00:18:32.654 --> 00:18:34.029
So. tip for everybody.

316
00:18:34.656 --> 00:18:36.699
don't miss it. please.

317
00:18:39.035 --> 00:18:41.412
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

318
00:18:58.388 --> 00:18:59.513
What are you doing down here?

319
00:19:00.265 --> 00:19:02.182
I could ask you the same thing.

320
00:19:03.435 --> 00:19:05.936
Why does a geological mapping mission
need explosives?

321
00:19:06.104 --> 00:19:08.063
You weren't listening in class.

322
00:19:08.231 --> 00:19:10.524
Seismic charges for the geological survey.

323
00:19:10.692 --> 00:19:12.401
Uh-huh. You believe that?

324
00:19:12.569 --> 00:19:13.861
I didn't say that.

325
00:19:14.654 --> 00:19:15.946
Have you met Colonel Packard yet?

326
00:19:16.114 --> 00:19:17.114
Yeah.

327
00:19:17.282 --> 00:19:18.866
The guy's wound pretty tight.

328
00:19:19.034 --> 00:19:22.369
Well. the man's a decorated war hero.
That's the package they come in.

329
00:19:23.038 --> 00:19:24.038
And you?

330
00:19:25.332 --> 00:19:28.334
Isn't shooting a mapping mission
a step down for a photojournalist?

331
00:19:28.543 --> 00:19:30.586
The right photo can help shape opinions.

332
00:19:30.754 --> 00:19:32.254
And win you a Pulitzer.

333
00:19:32.422 --> 00:19:34.631
Okay. Captain Conrad.

334
00:19:34.799 --> 00:19:35.799
What about you?

335
00:19:35.967 --> 00:19:38.302
How did British special forces
get dragged into this?

336
00:19:38.470 --> 00:19:41.430
- Just "Conrad." I'm decommissioned.
- Mmm-hmm.

337
00:19:42.140 --> 00:19:43.349
They offered me money.

338
00:19:43.516 --> 00:19:44.975
You don't strike me as a mercenary.

339
00:19:45.185 --> 00:19:46.977
You don't strike me as a war photographer.

340
00:19:47.604 --> 00:19:49.730
Anti-war photographer.

341
00:19:54.986 --> 00:19:56.987
(ROCK MUSIC PLAYING)

342
00:19:58.990 --> 00:20:00.783
(CAMERA CLICKING)

343
00:20:11.002 --> 00:20:12.127
What you writing there. Chap?

344
00:20:12.962 --> 00:20:13.962
Letter to my boy.

345
00:20:15.757 --> 00:20:17.674
Hmm. "Dear Billy.

346
00:20:17.842 --> 00:20:19.385
"I know I said I'd be home
by your birthday.

347
00:20:19.552 --> 00:20:21.178
"but I lied straight to your face.

348
00:20:21.346 --> 00:20:22.638
"I'm a terrible dad.

349
00:20:22.806 --> 00:20:24.264
"I hope this letter makes up for it."

350
00:20:25.433 --> 00:20:27.101
- That's too short.
- (LAUGHING)

351
00:20:32.732 --> 00:20:33.941
(CAMERA CLICKS)

352
00:20:49.207 --> 00:20:51.291
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

353
00:20:52.961 --> 00:20:53.961
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

354
00:20:54.170 --> 00:20:56.630
NIEVES: This storm looks
a lot nastier in person.

355
00:20:56.798 --> 00:20:59.049
Maybe we should consider
postponing the mission.

356
00:20:59.217 --> 00:21:00.843
How far away is this island?

357
00:21:01.010 --> 00:21:02.845
50 miles. maybe more.

358
00:21:03.012 --> 00:21:04.346
Take us closer.

359
00:21:04.514 --> 00:21:06.181
You wanna launch. you do it from here.

360
00:21:06.349 --> 00:21:07.891
Can you punch through that. Colonel?

361
00:21:08.059 --> 00:21:09.852
- Our opening is now.
- Through this hole right here?

362
00:21:10.478 --> 00:21:11.728
RANDA: Yeah.
it's a rare low-pressure pocket.

363
00:21:12.230 --> 00:21:14.189
NIEVES: I appreciate your passion. Randa.

364
00:21:14.357 --> 00:21:16.316
but as Field Supervisor
of the controlling agency.

365
00:21:16.484 --> 00:21:18.694
I say we abort.
That's it. we're gonna abort.

366
00:21:18.862 --> 00:21:20.028
RANDA: Wise call.

367
00:21:20.530 --> 00:21:23.031
I'm sure the Landsat inspector
will be inspired by your courage.

368
00:21:23.199 --> 00:21:25.033
No. he'll be inspired by my common sense.

369
00:21:25.201 --> 00:21:26.493
This is only a map survey.

370
00:21:27.203 --> 00:21:29.329
To one of the last uncharted areas
on the face of the Earth.

371
00:21:29.497 --> 00:21:30.873
And you wanna call it on account of rain?

372
00:21:31.040 --> 00:21:32.499
Stay on the boat if you want to.

373
00:21:32.667 --> 00:21:35.377
It could be years
before we get another shot at this.

374
00:21:35.879 --> 00:21:39.214
I'm told your unit is capable of handling
inclement weather. Colonel.

375
00:21:39.883 --> 00:21:43.010
Why don't we leave it to Colonel Packard
to break the tie?

376
00:21:44.429 --> 00:21:47.222
NIEVES: There is no way
I'm getting on that helicopter.

377
00:21:52.854 --> 00:21:55.939
BROOKS: We did ask to arm those
helicopters. Shouldn't they know why?

378
00:21:56.107 --> 00:21:58.233
Why? And raise an alarm?

379
00:21:58.902 --> 00:22:00.903
Purely a precaution. Brooks.

380
00:22:02.780 --> 00:22:03.780
Right.

381
00:22:03.948 --> 00:22:05.741
MALE ANNOUNCER: (ON PA)
Two mikes till launch.

382
00:22:05.909 --> 00:22:08.243
Troops and civilians.
board assigned aircraft.

383
00:22:08.411 --> 00:22:10.037
Two mikes till launch.

384
00:22:10.914 --> 00:22:12.998
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

385
00:22:19.589 --> 00:22:20.964
MILLS: What's the old man
getting us into. Cole?

386
00:22:21.591 --> 00:22:24.468
Nothing he wouldn't do himself.
He's taking the lead.

387
00:22:24.636 --> 00:22:26.595
Doesn't he miss his bed? I miss my bed!

388
00:22:26.763 --> 00:22:28.931
- Don't you miss your bed?
- (BEEPS)

389
00:22:29.140 --> 00:22:30.599
Do you even have a bed. Cole?

390
00:22:32.727 --> 00:22:34.436
You got a bed. right?

391
00:22:35.438 --> 00:22:36.980
PACKARD: See you at the rendezvous.
Chapman.

392
00:22:37.148 --> 00:22:38.607
Yes. sir.

393
00:22:38.983 --> 00:22:40.943
ANNOUNCER: (ON PA) One mike 30.
Repeat. one mike 30 to launch.

394
00:22:48.368 --> 00:22:50.160
(INDISTINCT SHOUTING)

395
00:22:54.457 --> 00:22:57.417
Complete FOD walkdown and clear the deck.

396
00:22:57.585 --> 00:22:58.669
One mike to launch.

397
00:22:59.170 --> 00:23:00.170
COLE: Battery?
MILLS: Check.

398
00:23:00.338 --> 00:23:02.256
- COLE: Generator start?
- Check. check.

399
00:23:02.423 --> 00:23:04.424
- Engine start?
- Check three times.

400
00:23:06.427 --> 00:23:08.637
PACKARD: This is Fox Leader to Fox Group.

401
00:23:08.805 --> 00:23:10.430
It is time. once again.

402
00:23:10.598 --> 00:23:12.432
for the Griffin and ant show.

403
00:23:12.600 --> 00:23:14.643
As usual. remember.

404
00:23:14.811 --> 00:23:17.646
hold onto your butts!

405
00:23:19.315 --> 00:23:22.484
MALE ANNOUNCER: (ON PA) Attention. pilots.
You are cleared for takeoff.

406
00:23:23.319 --> 00:23:25.487
Launch. launch. launch.

407
00:23:28.366 --> 00:23:30.826
(SOLDIERS CHATTERING ON RADIO)

408
00:23:45.800 --> 00:23:47.467
PACKARD: (ON RADIO) Combat formation.

409
00:23:48.469 --> 00:23:50.053
Keep visual.

410
00:23:50.221 --> 00:23:52.472
Fox Five. let me know when you close.

411
00:23:55.184 --> 00:23:57.185
Fox Five is in the slot.

412
00:23:57.353 --> 00:23:58.353
Roger that.

413
00:23:58.980 --> 00:24:02.149
Fox team. form up on me. Keep it together!

414
00:24:07.196 --> 00:24:08.405
Let's do this!

415
00:24:17.874 --> 00:24:19.708
Maintain course.

416
00:24:19.876 --> 00:24:21.501
Nothing we haven't done before.

417
00:24:22.879 --> 00:24:24.129
"Dear Billy.

418
00:24:24.756 --> 00:24:27.549
"You ever looked into a hurricane
and decide.

419
00:24:27.717 --> 00:24:29.926
"'Maybe I should fly straight through it?'

420
00:24:30.094 --> 00:24:32.095
"Because that's what's about to happen."

421
00:24:34.724 --> 00:24:35.766
COLE: Dear Billy.

422
00:24:35.933 --> 00:24:37.559
You might wanna hang on.

423
00:24:38.144 --> 00:24:40.354
(SOLDIERS CHATTERING ON RADIO)

424
00:24:46.778 --> 00:24:48.111
(ALARM BLARING)

425
00:24:52.867 --> 00:24:53.909
(GRUNTS)

426
00:24:58.247 --> 00:25:00.165
- (ALARM BEEPING)
- (GRUNTING)

427
00:25:02.418 --> 00:25:04.044
PACKARD: Fox Leader to Fox Group.

428
00:25:04.212 --> 00:25:05.545
Switch to inertial navigation.

429
00:25:07.256 --> 00:25:09.591
And remember the story of Icarus.

430
00:25:09.759 --> 00:25:12.344
whose father gave him wings made of wax

431
00:25:12.553 --> 00:25:15.305
and warned him
not to fly too close to the sun.

432
00:25:15.890 --> 00:25:18.100
But the exhilaration was too great.

433
00:25:18.267 --> 00:25:20.602
so he flew higher and higher

434
00:25:21.229 --> 00:25:23.772
until the sun melted his wings

435
00:25:24.440 --> 00:25:26.483
and he fell into the sea.

436
00:25:27.944 --> 00:25:31.655
But the United States Army
is not an irresponsible father.

437
00:25:31.823 --> 00:25:35.742
So they gave us wings
of white-hot. cold-rolled

438
00:25:35.910 --> 00:25:37.786
Pennsylvania steel.

439
00:25:38.746 --> 00:25:42.124
Guaranteed not to melt.

440
00:25:57.432 --> 00:25:58.432
(LAUGHS)

441
00:26:22.999 --> 00:26:24.666
(EXHALES) Ooh!

442
00:26:28.379 --> 00:26:29.713
Oh. hey. that's pretty. huh?

443
00:26:35.303 --> 00:26:36.720
Let's take them down. low and level.

444
00:26:43.895 --> 00:26:46.021
(LAUGHS) Whoo!

445
00:26:52.361 --> 00:26:53.445
(CAMERA CLICKING)

446
00:27:11.547 --> 00:27:13.548
(ROCK MUSIC PLAYING)

447
00:27:19.013 --> 00:27:20.806
PACKARD: Fox Leader to Fox Group.

448
00:27:20.973 --> 00:27:23.391
Split up. survey your zones.

449
00:27:23.559 --> 00:27:25.894
Fox Seven. put Landsat on deck.

450
00:27:27.230 --> 00:27:29.356
Copy. Fox Leader.
Fox Three headed to Zone Six.

451
00:27:29.732 --> 00:27:30.899
Put us down over there.

452
00:27:31.734 --> 00:27:33.318
PACKARD: Everyone else.
stay with the team leader.

453
00:27:36.364 --> 00:27:37.531
SOLDIER: Move that gear
to our three o'clock.

454
00:27:37.698 --> 00:27:39.241
Let's go. let's move it!

455
00:27:41.577 --> 00:27:43.245
(SOLDIERS CHATTERING ON RADIO)

456
00:28:00.763 --> 00:28:02.556
Ready for seismic charges.

457
00:28:02.974 --> 00:28:03.974
SOLDIER: Roger that.

458
00:28:06.811 --> 00:28:08.270
PACKARD: Fox Group. let it fly.

459
00:28:13.609 --> 00:28:15.443
(SOLDIER WHOOPING)

460
00:28:17.280 --> 00:28:19.781
PILOT: Copy all. Fox Three. Heading 0-9-0.

461
00:28:22.410 --> 00:28:23.785
Are you seeing what I'm seeing?

462
00:28:24.954 --> 00:28:28.456
The seismic response is incredible.

463
00:28:37.633 --> 00:28:39.843
Hey. Randa. you're not gonna believe this.

464
00:28:40.011 --> 00:28:41.177
The bedrock.

465
00:28:42.138 --> 00:28:43.471
it's practically hollow.

466
00:28:55.318 --> 00:28:56.318
Incoming!

467
00:29:07.663 --> 00:29:08.747
(SOLDIERS GASP)

468
00:29:09.332 --> 00:29:10.373
Look out!

469
00:29:11.125 --> 00:29:12.542
(ALL SCREAMING)

470
00:29:16.088 --> 00:29:17.923
(PILOT CHATTERING INDISTINCTLY)

471
00:29:21.636 --> 00:29:23.053
(GRUNTING)

472
00:29:31.854 --> 00:29:33.813
(SOLDIERS GROANING)

473
00:29:36.150 --> 00:29:37.400
(SOLDIER EXCLAIMS IN FEAR)

474
00:29:41.864 --> 00:29:43.448
(GROWLING)

475
00:29:48.204 --> 00:29:49.996
- (SCREAMING)
- (YELPING)

476
00:29:53.334 --> 00:29:54.334
(ROARING)

477
00:29:54.502 --> 00:29:55.669
(SCREAMING)

478
00:29:57.546 --> 00:29:58.838
PACKARD: On guard. Fox Five!

479
00:29:59.006 --> 00:30:00.966
Fox Eight is down! Fox Four is down!

480
00:30:01.300 --> 00:30:02.884
Respond. Fox Three!

481
00:30:06.013 --> 00:30:07.722
(SOLDIERS CHATTERING ON RADIO)

482
00:30:10.226 --> 00:30:11.226
PILOT 1: Oh. my God!

483
00:30:11.394 --> 00:30:13.728
PILOT 2: Fox Seven moving
into position. three o'clock.

484
00:30:13.896 --> 00:30:15.563
PILOT 1: Does anybody know what that is?

485
00:30:15.731 --> 00:30:18.066
PILOT 3: I don't know. man. God damn...

486
00:30:18.234 --> 00:30:20.402
Three klicks west of Red LZ.

487
00:30:20.611 --> 00:30:21.903
PILOT 1: Jesus!
I've never seen anything like it!

488
00:30:22.071 --> 00:30:24.280
PILOT 4: Set a perimeter of300 meters.
Do not engage.

489
00:30:24.448 --> 00:30:26.241
PILOT 5: Roger. Climb 1.800.

490
00:30:27.034 --> 00:30:28.576
(PILOTS CONTINUE
PANICKED CHATTERING)

491
00:30:44.427 --> 00:30:45.552
Is that a monkey?

492
00:30:45.720 --> 00:30:47.137
PILOT 1: What the hell is that?

493
00:30:47.596 --> 00:30:49.139
PILOT 6: Somebody talk to me. man.

494
00:30:49.306 --> 00:30:51.474
PILOT 7: Turn right. heading 2-5-0.
Contact approach...

495
00:30:51.642 --> 00:30:53.018
PACKARD: Fox Leader to Fox Group.

496
00:30:53.185 --> 00:30:55.895
Form a perimeter. Ready gunner positions.

497
00:30:56.313 --> 00:31:00.066
PILOT 6: Holy shit! Look at that thing!
I'm freaking out here!

498
00:31:00.234 --> 00:31:02.318
PACKARD: Fox Leader to Fox Group.
Fire at will!

499
00:31:02.528 --> 00:31:03.820
(ROARING)

500
00:31:05.656 --> 00:31:07.490
- What the hell is that?
- I don't know!

501
00:31:13.914 --> 00:31:15.665
(ROARING)

502
00:31:21.839 --> 00:31:23.131
(GRUNTS)

503
00:31:25.593 --> 00:31:26.634
Pull out now! Pull out!

504
00:31:26.802 --> 00:31:27.802
I don't take orders from you!

505
00:31:27.970 --> 00:31:28.970
Get us the hell out of here!

506
00:31:29.138 --> 00:31:30.388
- PILOT 8: Fox Nine is down!
- Whoa!

507
00:31:34.643 --> 00:31:36.686
Fox Six. we got nominal control.

508
00:31:36.854 --> 00:31:38.396
- (ALARM BEEPING)
- We are going down.

509
00:31:42.026 --> 00:31:43.151
(ROARS)

510
00:31:43.360 --> 00:31:46.362
PACKARD: Fox Five. this is Fox Leader.
Fox Nine is down.

511
00:31:46.530 --> 00:31:48.364
one klick north of river bend.

512
00:31:48.532 --> 00:31:50.533
Insert recovery team. Over.

513
00:31:50.701 --> 00:31:51.785
COLE: Fox Five is hovering.

514
00:31:53.204 --> 00:31:54.704
We got men going out the door!

515
00:31:55.581 --> 00:31:57.332
(PILOTS CHATTERING
INDISTINCTLY ON RADIO)

516
00:31:57.833 --> 00:31:59.125
PILOT 9: I need help here. I need...

517
00:31:59.502 --> 00:32:00.543
Oh. shit!

518
00:32:03.714 --> 00:32:05.715
(ROARING)

519
00:32:08.969 --> 00:32:10.386
Kill this son of a bitch.

520
00:32:10.554 --> 00:32:12.347
PILOT 6: Coming in hot! I got eyes on it!

521
00:32:12.598 --> 00:32:14.432
Pull up! (GROANS)

522
00:32:20.815 --> 00:32:23.149
- (ALARM BLARING)
- Brace for impact!

523
00:32:29.073 --> 00:32:30.698
PILOTS: Mayday. mayday!

524
00:32:32.451 --> 00:32:34.035
Run to the side. you idiot!

525
00:32:38.499 --> 00:32:40.041
(ALL GASPING)

526
00:32:42.545 --> 00:32:43.545
(SOLDIER SCREAMING)

527
00:32:43.754 --> 00:32:45.755
- Hang on!
- Watch out!

528
00:32:47.216 --> 00:32:48.716
(ALL YELP)

529
00:32:49.510 --> 00:32:50.885
- SLIVKO: Oh. God!
- Ahh!

530
00:32:53.180 --> 00:32:54.764
Prepare to crash!

531
00:32:54.932 --> 00:32:56.057
Brace!

532
00:32:59.937 --> 00:33:01.020
(ALL GRUNT)

533
00:33:03.357 --> 00:33:04.649
(ROARING)

534
00:33:04.900 --> 00:33:06.192
COLE: Fox Leader is down!

535
00:33:06.360 --> 00:33:08.027
Fox Five inbound for pickup!

536
00:33:08.195 --> 00:33:09.445
We have him in sight!

537
00:33:09.613 --> 00:33:12.532
Hold tight. Colonel Packard.
we are on our way!

538
00:33:13.826 --> 00:33:16.077
(GRUNTING)

539
00:33:16.453 --> 00:33:17.537
(STRAINING)

540
00:33:17.746 --> 00:33:19.581
PACKARD: Hang on. Briggs. I'm coming.

541
00:33:22.126 --> 00:33:24.169
(BRIGGS SCREAMING)

542
00:33:27.798 --> 00:33:29.048
(KONG ROARING)

543
00:33:32.428 --> 00:33:33.636
COLE: We're going down!

544
00:33:33.804 --> 00:33:35.889
I repeat. we are going down!

545
00:33:38.225 --> 00:33:40.476
Listen. I want you to tell me something
right now.

546
00:33:40.644 --> 00:33:42.270
- Do you love your mama?
- MILLS: I love her!

547
00:33:42.438 --> 00:33:44.772
- How much do you love your mama?
- I love my mama so much!

548
00:33:58.787 --> 00:33:59.996
(SOLDIERS SCREAMING)

549
00:34:09.256 --> 00:34:10.465
(INAUDIBLE)

550
00:34:24.021 --> 00:34:25.897
(SCREAMING)

551
00:34:46.794 --> 00:34:48.836
(ROARING)

552
00:35:06.855 --> 00:35:09.190
SLIVKO: Calling all units!
Is anybody airborne?

553
00:35:09.358 --> 00:35:11.567
I repeat. is anybody airborne?

554
00:35:12.403 --> 00:35:15.363
They're all down. Every one of them.

555
00:35:16.365 --> 00:35:18.199
We're on the south side of the island.

556
00:35:18.367 --> 00:35:20.326
There's a river
a couple of klicks from here.

557
00:35:20.494 --> 00:35:23.538
If we stick to its banks. we'll make it
to the exfil site on the north shore.

558
00:35:23.706 --> 00:35:26.708
And then what? All our choppers are down.

559
00:35:26.875 --> 00:35:28.376
We'll find a way to signal the ship.

560
00:35:28.544 --> 00:35:30.253
They'll send a search party.

561
00:35:30.421 --> 00:35:32.797
We just have to make it
by the exit window.

562
00:35:33.382 --> 00:35:35.091
I should be sitting at a desk.

563
00:35:35.718 --> 00:35:37.385
So. wait. are we just
not gonna talk about this?

564
00:35:37.886 --> 00:35:40.430
My best guess is we're scattered
over a four to five mile radius.

565
00:35:40.597 --> 00:35:43.016
We should head north
and join anyone we find.

566
00:35:43.183 --> 00:35:44.267
Are you all right?

567
00:35:44.435 --> 00:35:46.227
I don't know how to answer that question
right now.

568
00:35:46.395 --> 00:35:48.229
I don't know what that was either.

569
00:35:48.397 --> 00:35:51.357
All that money that they paid you?
I hope you're worth it.

570
00:35:52.067 --> 00:35:54.068
SLIVKO: We're really
not gonna talk about it?

571
00:35:54.236 --> 00:35:57.238
You know this is not normal. right?
Stuff like that doesn't just happen!

572
00:35:59.366 --> 00:36:01.117
PACKARD: This is Fox Leader to Fox Group!

573
00:36:01.285 --> 00:36:04.871
Anybody with ears. come back.
Respond. Over.

574
00:36:05.039 --> 00:36:06.581
Fox. Chapman.

575
00:36:06.749 --> 00:36:08.041
PACKARD: Fox Six. Chapman.

576
00:36:08.208 --> 00:36:09.250
Say again. your last.

577
00:36:09.418 --> 00:36:11.836
Four klicks west. highest peak...

578
00:36:12.004 --> 00:36:14.422
November Alpha 3. 0. 0. Over.

579
00:36:14.590 --> 00:36:17.592
Roger that. Chapman.
West highest mountain peak.

580
00:36:17.760 --> 00:36:18.760
Over.

581
00:36:18.927 --> 00:36:21.554
Fox Six confirm.
we're at the Sea Stallion.

582
00:36:21.722 --> 00:36:24.057
Chapman. hold your position.

583
00:36:24.224 --> 00:36:25.975
We'll come to you.
There's enough munitions

584
00:36:26.143 --> 00:36:27.977
on that Sea Stallion to kill this thing.

585
00:36:28.145 --> 00:36:29.896
Survey your perimeter.

586
00:36:30.064 --> 00:36:32.148
Locate possible ambush sites. Over.

587
00:36:32.358 --> 00:36:33.900
(STATIC ON RADIO)

588
00:36:34.109 --> 00:36:35.109
Chapman.

589
00:36:37.571 --> 00:36:38.571
Reles.

590
00:36:38.739 --> 00:36:40.990
taking an R and R day. or you good to go?

591
00:36:41.158 --> 00:36:42.617
I'm good to go. sir.

592
00:36:42.826 --> 00:36:44.077
(BECKONS INDISTINCTLY)

593
00:36:46.455 --> 00:36:47.955
Chapman to all stations.

594
00:36:48.123 --> 00:36:49.457
Recon environment.

595
00:37:05.516 --> 00:37:06.974
MILLS: Cole. what's wrong with you?

596
00:37:07.142 --> 00:37:08.935
How you even got an appetite right now?

597
00:37:12.147 --> 00:37:13.606
Eating's for the living.

598
00:37:14.441 --> 00:37:17.318
We just got taken down
by a monkey the size of a building!

599
00:37:17.486 --> 00:37:18.486
Yeah.

600
00:37:19.988 --> 00:37:22.490
That was an unconventional encounter.

601
00:37:22.658 --> 00:37:25.618
Is that really all
your brain telling itself right now?

602
00:37:26.161 --> 00:37:27.453
There's no tactical precedence.

603
00:37:27.621 --> 00:37:29.831
We did the best we could in the situation.

604
00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:33.543
PACKARD: Griffin Co.!

605
00:37:40.175 --> 00:37:42.051
Thank God you guys are okay!

606
00:37:45.722 --> 00:37:47.306
COLE: Good to see you. sir.
MILLS: We're all right.

607
00:37:47.975 --> 00:37:49.308
How many left?

608
00:37:49.476 --> 00:37:51.102
Seven survivors.

609
00:37:51.270 --> 00:37:53.104
Seven confirmed KIA.

610
00:37:53.272 --> 00:37:55.189
Galleta. Saraf. and Hodges.

611
00:37:56.191 --> 00:37:57.400
Slivko and the rest are unknown.

612
00:38:07.369 --> 00:38:08.870
(SIGHS)

613
00:38:12.040 --> 00:38:13.374
Where's Randa?

614
00:38:16.253 --> 00:38:17.503
How you doing?

615
00:38:17.671 --> 00:38:18.796
I'm fine. Thank you.

616
00:38:18.964 --> 00:38:22.008
Good. Glad to hear it.
I was worried about you.

617
00:38:26.805 --> 00:38:30.892
You are going to tell me
everything I don't know.

618
00:38:31.059 --> 00:38:33.144
or I'm gonna blow your head off.

619
00:38:35.272 --> 00:38:37.398
Monsters exist.

620
00:38:37.566 --> 00:38:38.649
No shit.

621
00:38:39.443 --> 00:38:41.235
Nobody believed me.

622
00:38:41.403 --> 00:38:43.237
Yesterday. I was a crackpot.

623
00:38:43.906 --> 00:38:45.198
But today...

624
00:38:46.074 --> 00:38:48.868
So this was never about geology.

625
00:38:49.036 --> 00:38:51.662
You dropped those charges
to flush something out.

626
00:38:52.581 --> 00:38:53.581
Who are you?

627
00:38:53.749 --> 00:38:56.209
You heard of the USS Lawton?

628
00:38:56.376 --> 00:38:58.002
Neither did the public.

629
00:38:58.170 --> 00:39:02.215
Out of a thousand young men on that ship.
I was the only survivor.

630
00:39:02.382 --> 00:39:04.467
They told my family
she was sunk in battle.

631
00:39:04.635 --> 00:39:05.801
but I know what I saw.

632
00:39:05.969 --> 00:39:07.803
It had no conscience.

633
00:39:08.639 --> 00:39:10.932
No reasoning. just destroy.

634
00:39:11.099 --> 00:39:12.892
I spent the last 30 years

635
00:39:13.060 --> 00:39:16.103
trying to prove the truth
of what I learned that day.

636
00:39:16.897 --> 00:39:19.565
This planet doesn't belong to us.

637
00:39:19.733 --> 00:39:24.111
Ancient species owned this earth
long before mankind.

638
00:39:24.279 --> 00:39:26.364
And if we keep our heads
buried in the sand.

639
00:39:26.532 --> 00:39:27.823
they will take it back.

640
00:39:28.367 --> 00:39:30.076
My agency is known as Monarch.

641
00:39:30.244 --> 00:39:33.913
We specialize in the hunt for Massive
Unidentified Terrestrial Organisms.

642
00:39:34.081 --> 00:39:36.082
You knew that thing was out here?

643
00:39:36.250 --> 00:39:39.252
I'm sorry for your men. Colonel.
I truly am.

644
00:39:40.587 --> 00:39:43.256
Get us home. with proof.

645
00:39:44.091 --> 00:39:46.175
So we can send the cavalry.

646
00:39:58.230 --> 00:39:59.939
I am the cavalry.

647
00:40:01.233 --> 00:40:02.775
BROOKS: It's called
the Hollow Earth theory.

648
00:40:02.943 --> 00:40:04.569
Randa hired me

649
00:40:04.736 --> 00:40:06.320
because I wrote a paper

650
00:40:06.488 --> 00:40:09.574
substantiating what most people think
is a crackpot idea.

651
00:40:09.741 --> 00:40:13.244
That there are these
massive underground spaces

652
00:40:13.412 --> 00:40:15.454
- isolated from the surface world.
- Passageways.

653
00:40:15.622 --> 00:40:18.291
Randa believed
this island may be one of those.

654
00:40:18.458 --> 00:40:20.293
BROOKS: An emergence point
for whatever lives below.

655
00:40:21.086 --> 00:40:23.546
Ancient species like what we just saw.

656
00:40:23.714 --> 00:40:25.548
I thought he was out of his mind.

657
00:40:26.383 --> 00:40:27.842
This is Slivko. Do you read?

658
00:40:28.010 --> 00:40:29.010
Anybody out there?

659
00:40:29.177 --> 00:40:31.012
We're headed north to the exfil location.

660
00:40:31.179 --> 00:40:33.180
Everyone here
seems way too calm right now.

661
00:40:34.099 --> 00:40:35.600
Do you copy? Anybody?

662
00:40:35.767 --> 00:40:36.976
We're out of range. Slivko.

663
00:40:37.144 --> 00:40:38.144
Oh. shit.

664
00:40:38.312 --> 00:40:40.271
Save it for
when we get closer to the group.

665
00:40:41.148 --> 00:40:43.524
(BIRDS CALLING)

666
00:40:46.695 --> 00:40:48.237
(GASPING)

667
00:40:51.867 --> 00:40:53.284
CONRAD: Nobody move.

668
00:40:54.745 --> 00:40:55.870
(BELLOWING)

669
00:40:56.079 --> 00:40:57.079
Easy.

670
00:41:01.335 --> 00:41:03.252
(SHUSHING)

671
00:41:12.929 --> 00:41:14.347
- CONRAD: Slivko.
- What?

672
00:41:15.724 --> 00:41:17.183
(SLIVKO BREATHING HEAVILY)

673
00:41:20.103 --> 00:41:21.437
Put it down.

674
00:41:26.652 --> 00:41:27.902
(CAMERA CLICKS)

675
00:41:43.794 --> 00:41:46.420
These men did not die in vain.

676
00:41:47.172 --> 00:41:49.173
I swear to God.

677
00:41:49.341 --> 00:41:53.344
their deaths will not go unanswered.

678
00:41:57.891 --> 00:41:59.892
Now let's get to Chapman
and those munitions.

679
00:42:09.194 --> 00:42:11.612
You ever heard the story of the mouse.
the lion. and the thorn?

680
00:42:12.364 --> 00:42:13.447
Yeah.

681
00:42:13.615 --> 00:42:14.824
There you go then.

682
00:42:14.991 --> 00:42:17.076
In case we ever see that primate again.

683
00:42:17.994 --> 00:42:20.955
You do know that story is about a mouse
becoming friends with the lion

684
00:42:21.123 --> 00:42:23.499
after taking the thorn out of his paw
though. right?

685
00:42:24.835 --> 00:42:26.293
No. it's not.

686
00:42:26.461 --> 00:42:28.713
The mouse kills the lion with the thorn.

687
00:42:28.922 --> 00:42:30.047
(MOSQUITOS BUZZING)

688
00:42:30.257 --> 00:42:31.757
Who told you that. Cole?

689
00:42:32.801 --> 00:42:34.218
My mother.

690
00:42:39.057 --> 00:42:40.599
That actually explains a lot.

691
00:42:45.647 --> 00:42:46.647
(GASPS)

692
00:43:07.586 --> 00:43:09.003
MILLS: Look out! Oh. shit!

693
00:43:09.171 --> 00:43:10.504
COLE: Watch out!
RELES: What is it?

694
00:43:10.672 --> 00:43:12.673
MILLS: Watch your six!
COLE: Up above!

695
00:43:12.841 --> 00:43:14.800
- MILLS: Up in the trees!
- Guns up!

696
00:43:20.474 --> 00:43:21.724
(GASPING)

697
00:43:21.975 --> 00:43:22.975
Cole!

698
00:43:23.393 --> 00:43:24.393
- No. no!
- Mills!

699
00:43:25.312 --> 00:43:26.312
We got you!

700
00:43:27.564 --> 00:43:28.689
I can't get a shot!

701
00:43:29.149 --> 00:43:30.775
(GRUNTING)

702
00:43:33.445 --> 00:43:36.322
Cut the legs! Cut it off at the legs!

703
00:43:37.574 --> 00:43:38.741
(YELPING)

704
00:43:45.874 --> 00:43:46.874
(SNARLING)

705
00:43:53.173 --> 00:43:55.007
(SCREAMING)

706
00:43:55.217 --> 00:43:56.425
(GROANS)

707
00:44:05.268 --> 00:44:06.352
I got you!

708
00:44:07.062 --> 00:44:09.063
- Go!
- (MILLS SCREAMING)

709
00:44:32.587 --> 00:44:35.422
PACKARD: Shake it off. guys!
Let's move out.

710
00:44:35.966 --> 00:44:37.341
(CREATURE SNARLING
IN DISTANCE)

711
00:44:40.345 --> 00:44:41.345
CONRAD: Stay tight.

712
00:44:48.228 --> 00:44:49.770
What the hell is this?

713
00:45:34.900 --> 00:45:35.941
(GASPS)

714
00:45:36.359 --> 00:45:37.693
SLIVKO: Oh! Behind you!

715
00:45:38.528 --> 00:45:39.570
CONRAD: Everybody. stay calm. Stay calm.

716
00:45:39.738 --> 00:45:40.821
WEAVER: Conrad.

717
00:45:40.989 --> 00:45:42.364
BROOKS: Stay back!

718
00:45:42.949 --> 00:45:43.991
- Guys.
- Stop. stop.

719
00:45:44.618 --> 00:45:46.201
CONRAD: Whoa. whoa. whoa!
SLIVKO: Stop. stop!

720
00:45:46.369 --> 00:45:47.453
Nobody shoot!

721
00:45:56.046 --> 00:45:57.046
(COCKS GUN)

722
00:45:57.255 --> 00:45:58.422
Whoa. whoa. whoa.

723
00:45:59.215 --> 00:46:00.758
No. no. no. No need for that.

724
00:46:00.926 --> 00:46:02.092
Come on now!

725
00:46:02.260 --> 00:46:04.219
Everybody. keep your wigs on now!

726
00:46:06.014 --> 00:46:07.014
What?

727
00:46:07.891 --> 00:46:09.850
I didn't believe it
when they said you were coming.

728
00:46:11.144 --> 00:46:12.227
I was up all night

729
00:46:12.395 --> 00:46:15.439
just thinking about how me and Gunpei
dreamed of this moment.

730
00:46:16.316 --> 00:46:17.524
And now here it is.

731
00:46:17.692 --> 00:46:19.860
28 years. 11 months

732
00:46:20.028 --> 00:46:22.488
and eight failed attempts
to get back to the world.

733
00:46:22.656 --> 00:46:24.448
and instead the world comes to me?

734
00:46:24.658 --> 00:46:26.367
(CHUCKLING) Ain't that a crack?

735
00:46:28.536 --> 00:46:29.912
They never smile.

736
00:46:30.664 --> 00:46:32.164
Did you crash here?

737
00:46:32.540 --> 00:46:34.375
Oh. Sorry. miss.

738
00:46:34.542 --> 00:46:37.294
Lieutenant Hank Marlow of the 45th.

739
00:46:37.963 --> 00:46:39.588
Put the old flight suit on for you.

740
00:46:39.965 --> 00:46:41.256
(MARLOW CHUCKLING)

741
00:46:42.884 --> 00:46:45.469
You are more beautiful

742
00:46:45.637 --> 00:46:48.222
than a hot dog and a beer

743
00:46:48.390 --> 00:46:51.058
at Wrigley Field on opening day.

744
00:46:57.524 --> 00:46:59.358
But you're real.

745
00:47:01.695 --> 00:47:02.695
Right?

746
00:47:05.115 --> 00:47:07.032
I told you. Didn't I tell you?

747
00:47:07.200 --> 00:47:08.367
I said.

748
00:47:08.535 --> 00:47:09.827
"It's fine."

749
00:47:11.371 --> 00:47:13.080
There we go.

750
00:47:17.002 --> 00:47:18.585
There's something out there. man.

751
00:47:18.753 --> 00:47:20.254
Oh. there's a lot out there.

752
00:47:21.589 --> 00:47:23.424
Now. come on. We gotta get home.

753
00:47:23.842 --> 00:47:26.176
You don't wanna be out here at night.
(CHUCKLES)

754
00:47:26.678 --> 00:47:29.138
(BIRDS CAWING)

755
00:47:40.316 --> 00:47:41.900
(GROANING SOFTLY)

756
00:47:45.363 --> 00:47:47.322
(RUSTLING)

757
00:48:23.818 --> 00:48:25.486
(CHITTERING SOFTLY)

758
00:48:37.582 --> 00:48:39.291
(GROANS)

759
00:49:10.573 --> 00:49:12.282
(GROWLING)

760
00:49:21.918 --> 00:49:23.502
(ROARING)

761
00:49:34.931 --> 00:49:36.306
(CHAPMAN YELPS)

762
00:50:09.591 --> 00:50:10.966
(PANTING)

763
00:50:17.015 --> 00:50:20.267
MARLOW: You probably noticed
a lot of weird things on this island.

764
00:50:21.477 --> 00:50:24.980
As long as we stay in here
where the people live. we'll be all right.

765
00:50:26.316 --> 00:50:27.524
That wall.

766
00:50:28.067 --> 00:50:30.360
is that supposed to keep out that thing?

767
00:50:31.446 --> 00:50:33.906
No. he's not the one
they're trying to keep out.

768
00:50:34.782 --> 00:50:36.033
What?

769
00:50:36.201 --> 00:50:39.620
MARLOW: These people live up on top of
the trees while we're down on the roots.

770
00:50:39.787 --> 00:50:41.330
Some of them don't even seem to age.

771
00:50:42.790 --> 00:50:44.166
There's no crime.

772
00:50:44.334 --> 00:50:46.126
no personal property.

773
00:50:46.628 --> 00:50:48.003
They're past all that.

774
00:51:00.892 --> 00:51:03.060
Thank you. Thank you.

775
00:51:04.771 --> 00:51:06.647
So. good news.

776
00:51:06.814 --> 00:51:08.815
They say you can shack up here.

777
00:51:10.610 --> 00:51:12.402
I didn't hear them say anything.

778
00:51:12.570 --> 00:51:14.655
Oh. they don't speak too much.

779
00:51:14.822 --> 00:51:18.784
When you've been here as long as I have.
you start to understand. You'll see.

780
00:51:18.952 --> 00:51:20.118
Wait a minute. Wait. wait. wait.

781
00:51:20.286 --> 00:51:22.788
We can't stay here.
We have to get off the island.

782
00:51:22.956 --> 00:51:24.498
We have lives. I have a life.

783
00:51:24.666 --> 00:51:27.542
Nieves. now is not the time. All right?

784
00:51:27.710 --> 00:51:29.711
What lands here tends to stay here.

785
00:51:31.965 --> 00:51:33.131
As far as I can tell.

786
00:51:33.299 --> 00:51:36.176
this ship washed up
about 10 years before I did.

787
00:51:36.344 --> 00:51:38.804
- WEAVER: You've been here since '44?
- Yeah.

788
00:51:38.972 --> 00:51:41.056
What happened with the war? Did we win?

789
00:51:41.224 --> 00:51:42.224
SLIVKO: Which one?

790
00:51:42.475 --> 00:51:44.768
MARLOW: Uh-huh. That makes sense.

791
00:51:46.312 --> 00:51:47.396
This is all hallowed ground to them.

792
00:51:47.563 --> 00:51:49.773
So if you like your hands.
don't touch anything.

793
00:52:03.204 --> 00:52:04.329
Oh!

794
00:52:05.581 --> 00:52:07.082
Look at that.

795
00:52:21.472 --> 00:52:23.890
MARLOW: The way they tell it.
for thousands of years.

796
00:52:24.058 --> 00:52:26.476
the people on this island lived in fear.

797
00:52:28.271 --> 00:52:30.897
That's a hell of a long time to be scared.

798
00:52:34.444 --> 00:52:37.404
And then. one day.
the damnedest thing happened.

799
00:52:37.572 --> 00:52:39.448
Some of the things they were afraid of

800
00:52:39.615 --> 00:52:42.784
started protecting them
against the things that were eating them.

801
00:52:44.912 --> 00:52:47.122
But nothing lasts forever. I guess.

802
00:52:53.713 --> 00:52:56.840
And this is where they honor
the last of their saviors.

803
00:53:03.973 --> 00:53:05.057
Yeah.

804
00:53:06.267 --> 00:53:07.517
That's Kong.

805
00:53:11.522 --> 00:53:13.357
He's king around here.

806
00:53:15.943 --> 00:53:17.778
He's God to these people.

807
00:53:19.781 --> 00:53:21.823
Kong's a pretty good king.

808
00:53:22.325 --> 00:53:24.159
Keeps to himself mostly.

809
00:53:27.205 --> 00:53:30.874
This is his home. We're just guests here.

810
00:53:32.543 --> 00:53:35.712
But you don't go into someone's house
and start dropping bombs

811
00:53:35.880 --> 00:53:37.381
unless you're picking a fight.

812
00:53:38.257 --> 00:53:40.509
Wasn't Kong the one
who killed your friend?

813
00:53:42.220 --> 00:53:43.220
No.

814
00:53:45.014 --> 00:53:46.264
One of them did.

815
00:53:47.934 --> 00:53:50.602
Kong's god on the island.

816
00:53:50.770 --> 00:53:52.854
but the devils live below us.

817
00:53:54.232 --> 00:53:55.565
And what are they called?

818
00:53:57.610 --> 00:53:59.236
The Iwis won't speak their name.

819
00:54:01.030 --> 00:54:02.489
But I call them Skull-crawlers.

820
00:54:02.657 --> 00:54:03.824
Why?

821
00:54:04.367 --> 00:54:05.617
'Cause it sounds neat.

822
00:54:08.496 --> 00:54:09.538
Okay.

823
00:54:09.705 --> 00:54:12.165
Look. I just made that name up.
I'm trying to scare you.

824
00:54:12.333 --> 00:54:13.375
I'm fine calling them that.

825
00:54:13.543 --> 00:54:14.751
- Are you cool with that?
- Yeah...

826
00:54:14.919 --> 00:54:16.294
- I like the name. so...
- That seems like a great name.

827
00:54:16.796 --> 00:54:20.382
I've never said that name out loud before.
It sounds stupid now that I say it.

828
00:54:20.550 --> 00:54:22.050
You call them whatever you want.

829
00:54:22.552 --> 00:54:25.011
They're big lizard things. Nasty.

830
00:54:26.055 --> 00:54:27.889
They come from the vents deep down.

831
00:54:28.057 --> 00:54:29.933
That's why Kong got so mad.

832
00:54:30.852 --> 00:54:31.852
(ROARS)

833
00:54:32.520 --> 00:54:34.521
Those bombs woke up a bunch of them.

834
00:54:38.025 --> 00:54:40.360
I tell you what.
You're lucky he's out there. too.

835
00:54:40.528 --> 00:54:42.195
or you wouldn't have made it this far.

836
00:54:43.239 --> 00:54:45.449
They're crafty bastards. Mean as hell.

837
00:54:50.872 --> 00:54:51.955
Now. he can handle them

838
00:54:52.123 --> 00:54:54.541
as long as he gets to them
when they're still small.

839
00:54:56.544 --> 00:54:57.544
(ROARS)

840
00:54:58.045 --> 00:55:00.046
You don't wanna wake up the big one.

841
00:55:00.214 --> 00:55:01.465
- How big is it?
- It's bigger.

842
00:55:02.049 --> 00:55:03.842
It wiped out his whole family.

843
00:55:04.010 --> 00:55:06.636
Kong's the last of his kind.
but he's still growing.

844
00:55:06.804 --> 00:55:08.305
And you better hope he does.

845
00:55:08.473 --> 00:55:10.432
Because the Iwis say once Kong goes.

846
00:55:10.600 --> 00:55:12.726
then the big one comes up.

847
00:55:14.353 --> 00:55:16.062
Then it's. "Goodnight. Irene."
(CHUCKLES)

848
00:55:16.939 --> 00:55:18.690
Listen. there's a refueling team

849
00:55:18.858 --> 00:55:21.401
coming to the north end of the island
in three days.

850
00:55:21.569 --> 00:55:23.111
You should come with us.

851
00:55:23.279 --> 00:55:24.905
To the north end of the island?

852
00:55:26.240 --> 00:55:27.282
- (LAUGHING)
- We're gonna get out of here.

853
00:55:27.450 --> 00:55:29.075
- In three days?
- Yes.

854
00:55:29.327 --> 00:55:31.077
(BOTH LAUGH)

855
00:55:35.166 --> 00:55:37.542
You can't get to the north end
in three days.

856
00:55:37.710 --> 00:55:40.587
It's impossible. That's it. No way.

857
00:55:44.509 --> 00:55:46.092
At least not on foot.

858
00:55:48.095 --> 00:55:50.096
(FLIES BUZZING)

859
00:56:02.818 --> 00:56:04.361
(CREATURE CALLING)

860
00:56:05.279 --> 00:56:06.530
(RIFLE CLICKS)

861
00:56:08.991 --> 00:56:12.536
(SCOFFS) That is one ugly ass bird.

862
00:56:18.668 --> 00:56:20.210
(CREATURES SCREECHING)

863
00:56:29.053 --> 00:56:30.345
RELES: Dear Billy.

864
00:56:30.513 --> 00:56:32.264
this place is hell.

865
00:56:34.642 --> 00:56:36.309
MILLS: And monsters exist.

866
00:56:36.477 --> 00:56:38.645
Under beds and signing paychecks.

867
00:56:39.480 --> 00:56:40.814
- Come on. man.
- Seems like

868
00:56:40.982 --> 00:56:44.609
maybe he wants to go kill that ape instead
of getting us off this island? Yeah!

869
00:56:44.777 --> 00:56:45.819
Are we even gonna make it?

870
00:56:45.987 --> 00:56:47.404
- Make what?
- The exfil!

871
00:56:47.572 --> 00:56:49.197
We gotta be there in three days!

872
00:56:49.365 --> 00:56:50.740
We'll make it. We're gonna make it.

873
00:56:50.908 --> 00:56:52.576
Yeah. but. Cole. what happens
if Chapman's not...

874
00:56:53.536 --> 00:56:55.829
The Colonel said he's there. he's there.

875
00:57:01.544 --> 00:57:03.503
MARLOW: We were this close
to getting it working.

876
00:57:03.671 --> 00:57:07.048
Me and Gunpei were gonna take off
for the open sea. try to get home.

877
00:57:07.216 --> 00:57:09.050
That's when one of them things got him.

878
00:57:12.221 --> 00:57:13.638
There she is.

879
00:57:24.650 --> 00:57:26.151
Well. that's lovely.

880
00:57:28.988 --> 00:57:30.405
You're damn right.

881
00:57:38.998 --> 00:57:40.707
Does this thing even float?

882
00:57:41.208 --> 00:57:44.628
Me and Gunpei spent six years
of our lives building this thing.

883
00:57:45.796 --> 00:57:47.714
She's called the Grey Fox.

884
00:57:47.882 --> 00:57:49.257
And she floats.

885
00:57:59.268 --> 00:58:01.061
Pulled the engine parts from my P-51

886
00:58:01.228 --> 00:58:02.729
and his old Zero.

887
00:58:02.897 --> 00:58:05.273
Found a B-29 on the beach one day.
That was something.

888
00:58:05.441 --> 00:58:07.025
You gotta be kidding me.

889
00:58:07.193 --> 00:58:09.611
That thing looks like
it's made out of pure tetanus.

890
00:58:11.072 --> 00:58:12.572
I know she ain't pretty to look at.

891
00:58:12.740 --> 00:58:15.283
but it's nothing
a couple of extra hands can't fix.

892
00:58:15.451 --> 00:58:18.328
Unless you got a better idea.
I suggest we get cracking.

893
00:58:21.040 --> 00:58:22.040
All right.

894
00:58:23.376 --> 00:58:25.418
(FOLK MUSIC PLAYING)

895
00:58:34.303 --> 00:58:35.303
(CAMERA CLICKS)

896
00:58:51.278 --> 00:58:52.278
(CAMERA CLICKS)

897
00:58:55.116 --> 00:58:57.617
(CREATURE BELLOWING
IN DISTANCE)

898
00:59:17.847 --> 00:59:19.514
(FLIES BUZZING)

899
00:59:31.444 --> 00:59:32.861
(BELLOWING IN PAIN)

900
00:59:50.838 --> 00:59:52.297
(GRUNTING)

901
00:59:57.762 --> 01:00:00.096
Come on. get up!

902
01:00:00.347 --> 01:00:01.514
(CONTINUES BELLOWING)

903
01:00:23.037 --> 01:00:24.704
(PANTING)

904
01:00:46.393 --> 01:00:47.685
(SIGHING IN RELIEF)

905
01:01:02.117 --> 01:01:03.993
(CREATURE SNARLING
IN DISTANCE)

906
01:01:06.247 --> 01:01:08.206
Well. would you look at that?

907
01:01:09.542 --> 01:01:10.708
It bleeds.

908
01:01:13.337 --> 01:01:15.088
- Wha...
- PACKARD: We did that.

909
01:01:15.297 --> 01:01:17.048
We hook up with Chapman.

910
01:01:17.216 --> 01:01:19.801
there's enough munitions
on that downed Sea Stallion

911
01:01:19.969 --> 01:01:21.719
to finish the job.

912
01:01:28.811 --> 01:01:30.103
Magnificent.

913
01:01:31.021 --> 01:01:33.439
You know why I carry this
instead of an M-16?

914
01:01:34.900 --> 01:01:37.610
Took it off a farmer fighting for the NVA.

915
01:01:37.778 --> 01:01:39.946
He surrendered
right after we leveled his village.

916
01:01:40.114 --> 01:01:41.656
He was 50 years old.

917
01:01:41.824 --> 01:01:43.533
Said he'd never even
seen a gun till we showed up.

918
01:01:43.742 --> 01:01:47.036
Sometimes. an enemy doesn't exist

919
01:01:48.247 --> 01:01:49.998
till you go looking for one.

920
01:01:50.791 --> 01:01:53.501
What happens when they show up
on your doorstep?

921
01:01:53.669 --> 01:01:55.336
I'll still have his gun.

922
01:01:57.006 --> 01:01:59.549
Best of luck with that. soldier.

923
01:02:06.515 --> 01:02:08.016
(ROCK MUSIC PLAYING)

924
01:02:08.475 --> 01:02:11.394
CONRAD: Okay. So. we've got 48 hours
to make it to the north shore.

925
01:02:11.562 --> 01:02:13.187
Slivko. do you know
what you're doing back there?

926
01:02:13.355 --> 01:02:14.939
SLIVKO: Yeah! My pop's a mechanic.

927
01:02:15.107 --> 01:02:16.274
If I can't fix this. he'll disown me.

928
01:02:17.693 --> 01:02:19.319
If he ever sees me again.

929
01:02:19.820 --> 01:02:21.237
Hold the phone there. Churchill.

930
01:02:21.405 --> 01:02:23.531
Russia was our ally.

931
01:02:23.699 --> 01:02:25.325
Now. you're saying we're at war with them?

932
01:02:25.492 --> 01:02:27.243
It's more of a cold war.

933
01:02:27.411 --> 01:02:28.703
Cold war like

934
01:02:28.871 --> 01:02:30.413
they take the summers off?

935
01:02:32.499 --> 01:02:35.001
What about the Cubs?
The Cubs win a World Series yet?

936
01:02:35.169 --> 01:02:36.169
The Cubs?

937
01:02:36.337 --> 01:02:37.503
Man. not even close.

938
01:02:37.671 --> 01:02:38.713
Were they ever good?

939
01:02:38.881 --> 01:02:40.381
Happens to be my team. Where are you from?

940
01:02:40.549 --> 01:02:41.591
- Detroit.
- Okay.

941
01:02:42.051 --> 01:02:44.844
Whoa. yeah. the Tigers.
Did they win at all this year?

942
01:02:45.012 --> 01:02:46.763
- I don't know.
- I doubt it. Yeah.

943
01:02:46.931 --> 01:02:48.514
I'd pick the Cubbies over the Tigers
any day.

944
01:02:48.682 --> 01:02:50.808
Who do you think would win in a fight?
A tiger or a cub?

945
01:02:51.727 --> 01:02:53.019
A tiger would win.

946
01:02:55.147 --> 01:02:56.356
Yeah. because a cub is a baby bear.

947
01:02:56.523 --> 01:02:58.524
A full-grown tiger can eat a baby bear.

948
01:03:00.361 --> 01:03:01.736
Just gotta think it through.

949
01:03:03.822 --> 01:03:05.365
We also put a man on the moon.

950
01:03:05.532 --> 01:03:07.241
No kidding?

951
01:03:07.409 --> 01:03:09.160
What did they do? Just leave him up there?

952
01:03:09.328 --> 01:03:10.870
What's he eating?

953
01:03:11.038 --> 01:03:13.206
Tang. Spam.

954
01:03:14.291 --> 01:03:15.333
Hmm.

955
01:03:15.626 --> 01:03:17.460
CONRAD: Come on. we're losing daylight.

956
01:03:23.092 --> 01:03:25.551
Fox Leader. this is Chapman. over.

957
01:03:26.595 --> 01:03:28.388
Fox Leader. this is Chapman. over.

958
01:03:28.806 --> 01:03:30.056
(STATIC ON RADIO)

959
01:03:37.314 --> 01:03:38.314
(SIGHS)

960
01:03:38.899 --> 01:03:40.108
Dear Billy...

961
01:03:41.235 --> 01:03:43.820
Sometimes.
life just punch you in the balls.

962
01:03:44.321 --> 01:03:45.363
Damn it.

963
01:03:48.993 --> 01:03:50.076
(GASPS)

964
01:03:53.580 --> 01:03:55.456
(TRILLING)

965
01:04:01.588 --> 01:04:03.423
(GROANING)

966
01:04:18.022 --> 01:04:19.230
(PANTING)

967
01:04:24.570 --> 01:04:25.987
(SNARLS)

968
01:04:33.537 --> 01:04:34.787
(ROCK MUSIC PLAYING)

969
01:04:36.123 --> 01:04:37.457
What kind of music is that?

970
01:04:38.292 --> 01:04:39.667
What happened to swing?

971
01:04:39.835 --> 01:04:40.960
Benny Goodman?

972
01:04:41.628 --> 01:04:43.004
You're like a time-traveler. man.

973
01:04:43.172 --> 01:04:44.964
I'm telling you. this is the new sound.

974
01:04:52.389 --> 01:04:54.891
I don't know if I'm gonna like
whoever's under this beard.

975
01:04:55.059 --> 01:04:58.478
I really hope that thing you call a boat
can get us upriver in 36 hours.

976
01:04:58.645 --> 01:05:00.563
Because if we miss that window.

977
01:05:01.482 --> 01:05:02.982
we're. literally. up a creek.

978
01:05:04.318 --> 01:05:06.861
When I first wrote that paper
on the Hollow Earth theory.

979
01:05:07.029 --> 01:05:09.072
the whole committee laughed out loud.

980
01:05:10.074 --> 01:05:11.407
Not Randa.

981
01:05:11.909 --> 01:05:15.328
The one guy in the crowd
who actually took me seriously.

982
01:05:15.496 --> 01:05:16.954
It felt good.

983
01:05:17.122 --> 01:05:19.499
Then I thought he was crazy when he said
the earth was full of monsters.

984
01:05:20.751 --> 01:05:22.376
I can't tell when I'm talking

985
01:05:22.544 --> 01:05:24.170
- or when I'm not talking.
- You're talking.

986
01:05:24.338 --> 01:05:25.338
- Am I?
- Yes.

987
01:05:25.506 --> 01:05:27.006
- I'm talking?
- Yes.

988
01:05:27.174 --> 01:05:28.341
Your mouth is moving.

989
01:05:28.509 --> 01:05:29.509
What?

990
01:05:29.676 --> 01:05:31.886
I'm gonna stab you
by the end of the night.

991
01:05:32.346 --> 01:05:33.346
Really?

992
01:05:33.597 --> 01:05:35.848
(CHUCKLES) Just kidding.

993
01:05:39.937 --> 01:05:42.355
MARLOW: If the boat doesn't work.
we'll just take the train.

994
01:05:43.857 --> 01:05:48.361
CONRAD: Isn't it odd the most dangerous
places are always the most beautiful?

995
01:05:49.655 --> 01:05:51.948
Mmm. I'm trying to take
a long-exposure photograph.

996
01:05:52.116 --> 01:05:53.449
but my flashlight broke.

997
01:05:54.493 --> 01:05:55.743
Oh. Um...

998
01:05:56.703 --> 01:05:57.703
Try this.

999
01:05:58.539 --> 01:05:59.539
Thank you.

1000
01:06:02.292 --> 01:06:04.293
- Royal Air Force?
- It was my father's.

1001
01:06:04.461 --> 01:06:07.922
He threw it to me from the train
as he rolled off to fight the Nazis.

1002
01:06:08.674 --> 01:06:10.758
He was like John Wayne to me.

1003
01:06:11.218 --> 01:06:13.010
Some kind of mythic hero.

1004
01:06:14.263 --> 01:06:15.763
Did he come back?

1005
01:06:15.931 --> 01:06:18.599
His plane went down near Hamburg.

1006
01:06:18.767 --> 01:06:20.768
They searched for him for months but...

1007
01:06:24.773 --> 01:06:27.400
I suppose no man comes home from war.

1008
01:06:28.735 --> 01:06:29.944
Not really.

1009
01:06:39.246 --> 01:06:42.415
COLE: Mills. quit dicking around.
I'm going on perimeter.

1010
01:06:53.427 --> 01:06:54.760
RANDA: Colonel Packard.

1011
01:06:57.055 --> 01:07:00.558
this mission to the crash site is folly.

1012
01:07:02.144 --> 01:07:04.604
I understand going after your man.

1013
01:07:05.647 --> 01:07:07.273
But the rest of it...

1014
01:07:08.817 --> 01:07:10.443
This is beyond us.

1015
01:07:11.904 --> 01:07:14.071
You don't like the way I'm running things?

1016
01:07:14.823 --> 01:07:16.824
You know where the door is.

1017
01:07:18.619 --> 01:07:21.913
You set this in motion
when you put this place on the map.

1018
01:07:22.080 --> 01:07:24.916
And I will not cut and run.

1019
01:07:27.628 --> 01:07:30.254
I know an enemy when I see it.

1020
01:07:58.158 --> 01:08:00.618
This man's name was Gunpei Ikari.

1021
01:08:03.664 --> 01:08:05.498
But you take away the uniforms

1022
01:08:06.166 --> 01:08:07.166
and the war...

1023
01:08:09.002 --> 01:08:10.836
He became my brother.

1024
01:08:13.507 --> 01:08:16.008
And we swore
we'd never leave each other behind.

1025
01:08:22.683 --> 01:08:24.350
Let's get off this island.

1026
01:08:33.235 --> 01:08:34.568
- (SPUTTERS)
- SLIVKO: Ow!

1027
01:08:34.820 --> 01:08:36.028
Not yet!

1028
01:08:36.196 --> 01:08:37.863
CONRAD: Prime the lines.
SLIVKO: Yeah. yeah. yeah.

1029
01:08:38.532 --> 01:08:39.865
CONRAD: Wind it up. let's go!

1030
01:08:40.909 --> 01:08:42.201
- SLIVKO: Keep going!
- (GRUNTS)

1031
01:08:43.120 --> 01:08:44.662
(GRUNTING)

1032
01:08:45.163 --> 01:08:46.372
(ENGINE SPUTTERS)

1033
01:08:46.707 --> 01:08:48.874
Third time's the charm.
Here we go. Here we go!

1034
01:08:50.043 --> 01:08:52.003
Let's go. let's go. let's go.

1035
01:08:52.170 --> 01:08:53.879
Come on. come on.

1036
01:08:55.173 --> 01:08:56.173
Yes.

1037
01:08:56.758 --> 01:08:58.384
(ENGINE STARTING)

1038
01:08:59.386 --> 01:09:00.386
(LAUGHS)

1039
01:09:00.887 --> 01:09:02.263
Yes! Yes!

1040
01:09:02.681 --> 01:09:04.557
(ALL LAUGHING)

1041
01:09:04.808 --> 01:09:05.808
(GASPS)

1042
01:09:27.456 --> 01:09:29.290
I guess this is goodbye.

1043
01:09:31.376 --> 01:09:32.585
Thank you.

1044
01:09:41.428 --> 01:09:43.971
If you're ever in Chicago.
look me up. I guess.

1045
01:09:51.938 --> 01:09:52.938
(CAMERA CLICKS)

1046
01:10:29.768 --> 01:10:31.560
(ROCK MUSIC PLAYING)

1047
01:11:11.768 --> 01:11:13.185
Here. no. Let me help.

1048
01:11:15.188 --> 01:11:16.856
Man's gotta do what... Ow!

1049
01:11:17.107 --> 01:11:18.107
Are you okay?

1050
01:11:18.275 --> 01:11:19.525
I'm okay.

1051
01:11:19.693 --> 01:11:21.444
- Allow me.
- (CHUCKLES)

1052
01:11:21.695 --> 01:11:23.529
You should see me in the library.

1053
01:11:26.408 --> 01:11:28.075
MARLOW: I got a wife.

1054
01:11:28.243 --> 01:11:29.285
Had a wife.

1055
01:11:29.453 --> 01:11:30.870
Have a wife?

1056
01:11:32.122 --> 01:11:33.539
Guess I don't know anymore.

1057
01:11:35.375 --> 01:11:37.084
We got hitched right before I deployed.

1058
01:11:37.627 --> 01:11:40.045
Got a telegram from her
the day before I got shot down.

1059
01:11:40.213 --> 01:11:41.755
She said we just had our baby boy.

1060
01:11:42.215 --> 01:11:43.257
I got a son out there.

1061
01:11:44.092 --> 01:11:46.051
Grown man I've never met.

1062
01:11:46.219 --> 01:11:47.970
Yeah. she definitely thinks
you're dead. man.

1063
01:11:48.221 --> 01:11:49.722
Hey!

1064
01:11:50.599 --> 01:11:51.599
I'm just saying.

1065
01:11:52.225 --> 01:11:53.642
CONRAD: You don't know that.

1066
01:11:53.810 --> 01:11:55.603
You'd be surprised how long people wait.

1067
01:11:55.937 --> 01:11:58.397
Ah. truth is.
I don't expect them to be waiting.

1068
01:11:59.107 --> 01:12:00.941
I'd be fine either way.

1069
01:12:02.152 --> 01:12:04.320
I just want one last chance to see them.

1070
01:12:06.198 --> 01:12:08.073
That'd be good enough for me.

1071
01:12:08.241 --> 01:12:09.408
WEAVER: We're gonna get you home.

1072
01:12:10.410 --> 01:12:11.660
MILLS: (ON RADIO)
Fox Five. come back.

1073
01:12:11.828 --> 01:12:12.912
Is there anyone out there?

1074
01:12:13.079 --> 01:12:14.622
Hey! This is Fox Five. We hear you.

1075
01:12:16.082 --> 01:12:17.500
Yeah! We're on a boat. We're on a boat

1076
01:12:17.667 --> 01:12:19.627
- headed up north on a river.
- A boat?

1077
01:12:19.794 --> 01:12:20.836
Where'd y'all get a boat?

1078
01:12:21.004 --> 01:12:23.631
We met this. like. crazy Santa Claus.
time-traveler guy

1079
01:12:23.798 --> 01:12:24.924
from World War II. You'll meet him.

1080
01:12:25.091 --> 01:12:26.342
What kind of boat y'all got?

1081
01:12:26.510 --> 01:12:28.260
It's more of. like. a plane
than a boat. really.

1082
01:12:28.428 --> 01:12:29.678
Let's call it a "ploat."

1083
01:12:29.846 --> 01:12:30.846
We're on a ploat.

1084
01:12:31.014 --> 01:12:32.348
We need their location. Slivko.

1085
01:12:32.516 --> 01:12:34.517
Send up a flare so we can find you.

1086
01:12:35.602 --> 01:12:36.810
Roger that. Fox Five.

1087
01:12:37.437 --> 01:12:38.812
Fire in the hole!

1088
01:12:44.027 --> 01:12:45.611
There!

1089
01:12:45.779 --> 01:12:47.363
- Yes!
- (ALL LAUGH)

1090
01:12:47.531 --> 01:12:49.865
SLIVKO: I repeat. we have a visual.
Two klicks to our north.

1091
01:12:50.033 --> 01:12:52.451
Roger that. Fox Five. Fox One out.

1092
01:12:54.120 --> 01:12:55.955
Rendezvous point. one hour.

1093
01:12:56.122 --> 01:12:57.122
Mount up!

1094
01:12:57.290 --> 01:12:58.832
Can we fit everybody?

1095
01:13:00.544 --> 01:13:01.627
Yes!

1096
01:13:02.087 --> 01:13:03.128
- We're going home!
- (ALL LAUGH)

1097
01:13:03.296 --> 01:13:04.797
(SCREAMING)

1098
01:13:05.006 --> 01:13:06.423
ALL: Whoa!

1099
01:13:10.136 --> 01:13:11.220
CONRAD: Get down!

1100
01:13:12.430 --> 01:13:14.348
(CONTINUES SCREAMING)

1101
01:13:21.648 --> 01:13:23.107
What the hell. man?

1102
01:13:23.608 --> 01:13:24.942
CONRAD: He's gone.

1103
01:13:25.110 --> 01:13:28.153
Everybody. grab your gear.
We have to keep moving.

1104
01:13:29.197 --> 01:13:30.990
We'll go ashore. meet up with Packard.

1105
01:13:31.157 --> 01:13:32.491
No. Wait a minute! Wait a minute!

1106
01:13:32.659 --> 01:13:34.868
Is nobody gonna say anything about the...

1107
01:13:35.036 --> 01:13:36.036
He's gone!

1108
01:13:36.204 --> 01:13:37.830
And he ain't coming back.
There's nothing to say.

1109
01:13:41.835 --> 01:13:43.002
BROOKS: Oh. my God.

1110
01:13:43.420 --> 01:13:44.670
(EXHALES DEEPLY)

1111
01:13:48.008 --> 01:13:50.050
CONRAD: Their flare
was only two klicks north.

1112
01:13:51.386 --> 01:13:52.803
They should be here soon.

1113
01:13:52.971 --> 01:13:55.681
Unless they were eaten by something
that's bigger than us.

1114
01:13:58.602 --> 01:14:00.144
(RUSTLING)

1115
01:14:02.689 --> 01:14:03.689
Holy shit!

1116
01:14:04.107 --> 01:14:05.608
MILLS: Slivko!

1117
01:14:05.775 --> 01:14:06.900
Thought you were taking a dirt nap
by now. Slivko.

1118
01:14:07.068 --> 01:14:08.360
Never thought I'd see you guys again.

1119
01:14:08.528 --> 01:14:10.738
- I thought you were crazy.
- I wish I had been.

1120
01:14:10.905 --> 01:14:12.823
- What's your count?
- What you see

1121
01:14:12.991 --> 01:14:13.991
is what I got.

1122
01:14:14.159 --> 01:14:15.200
We lost one. too.

1123
01:14:15.368 --> 01:14:16.368
Good to see you. fellas!

1124
01:14:17.203 --> 01:14:18.370
Who the hell is this?

1125
01:14:18.538 --> 01:14:19.538
We picked up a hitchhiker.

1126
01:14:20.206 --> 01:14:23.208
Lieutenant Hank Marlow of
the 45th Pursuit Squadron of the 15th.

1127
01:14:23.376 --> 01:14:25.377
You've been here since World War II?

1128
01:14:25.545 --> 01:14:27.713
Yes. sir. I miss the parade?

1129
01:14:28.381 --> 01:14:29.548
I'll be damned.

1130
01:14:29.716 --> 01:14:31.216
Snap to. Lieutenant.

1131
01:14:31.384 --> 01:14:32.635
CONRAD: We're gonna get him home. sir.

1132
01:14:33.219 --> 01:14:34.261
If we follow this river.

1133
01:14:34.429 --> 01:14:36.555
we'll make it to the boat. and we'll
make it to the north shore in time.

1134
01:14:36.723 --> 01:14:38.265
That sounds good.

1135
01:14:38.433 --> 01:14:39.725
But we're not leaving yet.

1136
01:14:39.893 --> 01:14:41.226
Still got a man out there. Conrad.

1137
01:14:42.228 --> 01:14:43.562
Wait a second. You got someone out there?

1138
01:14:43.730 --> 01:14:44.730
Chapman.

1139
01:14:44.898 --> 01:14:46.857
He's with the downed Sea Stallion
just west of here.

1140
01:14:47.025 --> 01:14:48.984
West? We can't go west!

1141
01:14:49.152 --> 01:14:50.736
That's where the skull things live.

1142
01:14:50.904 --> 01:14:53.238
We have an old saying here.
"East is best. west is worst!"

1143
01:14:53.406 --> 01:14:54.573
That's why we say it!

1144
01:14:54.741 --> 01:14:56.450
You know. southwest...

1145
01:14:56.618 --> 01:14:57.785
We could talk about that.

1146
01:14:57.952 --> 01:15:00.245
But you're gonna need a lot more guns
if you're gonna go west.

1147
01:15:00.830 --> 01:15:03.791
Guys. I think that
we should listen to Marlow.

1148
01:15:04.668 --> 01:15:06.335
This is crazy.

1149
01:15:07.045 --> 01:15:08.045
Hey.

1150
01:15:08.630 --> 01:15:12.091
Your job is finding lost men. right?

1151
01:15:15.637 --> 01:15:16.720
Okay. sir.

1152
01:15:16.888 --> 01:15:18.889
But if we reach that position
and he's not there.

1153
01:15:19.057 --> 01:15:20.140
we don't send out a search party.

1154
01:15:20.308 --> 01:15:22.267
We're back here by nightfall. understood?

1155
01:15:22.435 --> 01:15:24.561
In 24 hours. we have to be
on the other side of this island.

1156
01:15:24.729 --> 01:15:27.231
Roger that. Hear you loud and clear.

1157
01:15:27.399 --> 01:15:30.317
All right. you heard the man.
Moving out in 10.

1158
01:15:30.485 --> 01:15:32.069
MARLOW: This is a good group of boys.

1159
01:15:32.237 --> 01:15:34.154
We're all gonna die together out here.

1160
01:15:34.322 --> 01:15:37.408
You're a good group of boys to die with.
I'll tell you that much.

1161
01:15:37.575 --> 01:15:39.326
(LAUGHS) You shouldn't have come here.

1162
01:15:40.453 --> 01:15:42.621
Don't forget to tell me
this is a bad idea.

1163
01:15:43.123 --> 01:15:44.832
This is a bad idea.

1164
01:16:20.368 --> 01:16:21.618
MARLOW: Yeah. you smell that?

1165
01:16:22.328 --> 01:16:23.495
That's death.

1166
01:16:27.041 --> 01:16:28.834
SLIVKO: What the hell is this place?

1167
01:16:29.002 --> 01:16:31.336
MARLOW: This is what's left
of Kong's parents.

1168
01:16:31.504 --> 01:16:34.840
I've taken enough photos of mass graves
to recognize one.

1169
01:16:35.008 --> 01:16:37.384
The crash site's just on the other side
of this valley.

1170
01:16:37.552 --> 01:16:40.220
We'll cross through and
make it to the highest point west.

1171
01:16:40.388 --> 01:16:41.513
Uh-uh.

1172
01:16:42.182 --> 01:16:44.516
This place is a real no-no. sir.

1173
01:16:44.684 --> 01:16:46.101
We need to be going to the north side
right now.

1174
01:16:46.269 --> 01:16:49.688
And you're welcome to do that. my man.
By yourself.

1175
01:16:51.065 --> 01:16:54.026
I'm not leaving Jack out there.
Now. who's with me?

1176
01:16:55.195 --> 01:16:56.361
We can make it.

1177
01:16:56.905 --> 01:16:57.988
You're mighty right. we can make it.

1178
01:16:58.198 --> 01:17:00.783
Now. stay sharp. Keep an eye out.

1179
01:17:04.537 --> 01:17:06.872
I've only been here 28 years.
What do I know?

1180
01:17:24.265 --> 01:17:25.265
(CAMERA CLICKS)

1181
01:17:40.907 --> 01:17:43.909
Cole. we don't got time for that. man.
Put the cigarette out.

1182
01:17:56.256 --> 01:17:58.090
Watch those fumes!

1183
01:17:59.217 --> 01:18:01.635
- Idiots.
- (CAMERA CLICKS)

1184
01:18:02.595 --> 01:18:03.595
(PANTING)

1185
01:18:03.888 --> 01:18:05.722
PACKARD: Let's go. We gotta move!

1186
01:18:08.351 --> 01:18:10.435
(CREATURE SCREECHING
IN DISTANCE)

1187
01:18:14.274 --> 01:18:15.274
Run!

1188
01:18:19.779 --> 01:18:20.779
In here!

1189
01:18:22.574 --> 01:18:24.408
(BOTH PANTING)

1190
01:18:26.119 --> 01:18:27.119
RANDA: Quiet.

1191
01:18:31.583 --> 01:18:32.749
(WHIMPERS)

1192
01:18:34.919 --> 01:18:35.961
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

1193
01:18:36.129 --> 01:18:37.629
(CREATURE HISSING)

1194
01:18:45.847 --> 01:18:46.847
(ROARS)

1195
01:18:48.099 --> 01:18:50.309
I told you this damn place was a no-no.

1196
01:18:51.227 --> 01:18:52.644
- (CREATURE RETCHING)
- (GASPS)

1197
01:18:54.522 --> 01:18:55.522
Ugh!

1198
01:18:55.732 --> 01:18:56.815
Damn it.

1199
01:18:59.903 --> 01:19:01.361
(CONTINUES RETCHING)

1200
01:19:07.118 --> 01:19:08.327
(GASPS)

1201
01:19:09.495 --> 01:19:10.495
Oh.

1202
01:19:26.346 --> 01:19:27.346
All right. let's move.

1203
01:19:28.014 --> 01:19:29.264
Rally on me.

1204
01:19:31.517 --> 01:19:33.101
Rally up! Rally up!

1205
01:19:34.062 --> 01:19:36.521
Somebody cover the civilians' six.
Let's move!

1206
01:19:45.657 --> 01:19:46.657
(CLICKS)

1207
01:19:47.617 --> 01:19:49.826
(CLICKING)

1208
01:19:50.036 --> 01:19:51.036
Oh. shit.

1209
01:19:54.123 --> 01:19:55.123
Randa!

1210
01:19:57.794 --> 01:19:59.002
(YELLING)

1211
01:20:04.258 --> 01:20:05.258
Set up the 50!

1212
01:20:06.135 --> 01:20:07.552
(GUN COCKS)

1213
01:20:18.356 --> 01:20:19.356
(CAMERA CLICKS)

1214
01:20:22.235 --> 01:20:23.235
(CAMERA CLICKS)

1215
01:20:26.197 --> 01:20:27.197
- (GROWL)
- (SOLDIER GASPS)

1216
01:20:31.911 --> 01:20:32.911
(CAMERA CLICKS)

1217
01:20:33.121 --> 01:20:34.955
(SNIFFLING)

1218
01:20:36.332 --> 01:20:38.583
(CAMERA CONTINUES CLICKING)

1219
01:20:45.758 --> 01:20:46.800
(SPEAKING JAPANESE)

1220
01:20:52.265 --> 01:20:53.807
(ROARING)

1221
01:20:55.018 --> 01:20:56.018
Go!

1222
01:21:00.606 --> 01:21:01.606
(SCREAMING)

1223
01:21:03.776 --> 01:21:05.277
(GASPS)

1224
01:21:05.820 --> 01:21:07.195
(PANTING)

1225
01:21:13.786 --> 01:21:14.786
(GRUNTS)

1226
01:21:15.246 --> 01:21:16.872
- (SCREAMS)
- (SNARLS)

1227
01:21:17.623 --> 01:21:19.791
Bring the torch! Do your thing!

1228
01:21:21.878 --> 01:21:23.628
(CREATURE SCREECHING)

1229
01:21:34.432 --> 01:21:35.432
(SCREAMING)

1230
01:21:39.020 --> 01:21:40.020
(GROANS)

1231
01:21:41.898 --> 01:21:42.939
(GAS HISSING)

1232
01:21:43.900 --> 01:21:45.275
CONRAD: Slivko!

1233
01:21:45.443 --> 01:21:46.443
Gas!

1234
01:21:50.073 --> 01:21:51.364
(CREATURES SCREECHING)

1235
01:21:54.911 --> 01:21:56.328
(YELPING)

1236
01:21:57.163 --> 01:21:58.413
(SCREECHING)

1237
01:22:02.376 --> 01:22:03.376
(GROANS)

1238
01:22:03.836 --> 01:22:05.087
(GRUNTING)

1239
01:22:06.214 --> 01:22:08.256
Marlow! Sword!

1240
01:22:16.724 --> 01:22:18.642
(MUFFLED GRUNTING)

1241
01:22:33.866 --> 01:22:35.033
Slivko. hang on!

1242
01:22:36.077 --> 01:22:37.702
(SOLDIER SCREAMING)

1243
01:22:42.708 --> 01:22:44.000
This thing's moving!

1244
01:22:44.210 --> 01:22:45.210
Whoa!

1245
01:22:50.258 --> 01:22:51.258
(GRUNTS)

1246
01:22:55.471 --> 01:22:56.513
(ALL SCREAMING)

1247
01:22:57.598 --> 01:22:58.598
(BOTH GROAN)

1248
01:22:59.934 --> 01:23:01.726
(WEAVER GROANING)

1249
01:23:04.897 --> 01:23:05.897
(SCREECHES)

1250
01:23:07.400 --> 01:23:09.568
(ALL PANTING)

1251
01:23:15.074 --> 01:23:16.241
MARLOW: Now. look. Colonel.

1252
01:23:17.076 --> 01:23:19.077
You may outrank me.

1253
01:23:19.245 --> 01:23:21.913
but I've been here a hell of a lot longer.

1254
01:23:22.081 --> 01:23:23.415
And I'm telling you

1255
01:23:23.583 --> 01:23:26.918
that thing that just shredded us
was only the first of them.

1256
01:23:27.086 --> 01:23:28.670
Now we're on their turf.

1257
01:23:28.838 --> 01:23:31.590
and we need to turn back toot sweet!

1258
01:23:31.757 --> 01:23:33.675
Not as long as Chapman's still out there.

1259
01:23:33.843 --> 01:23:35.552
CONRAD: I'm sorry. Colonel Packard.

1260
01:23:36.762 --> 01:23:38.346
Chapman is dead.

1261
01:23:44.270 --> 01:23:45.520
Doesn't change a thing!

1262
01:23:45.688 --> 01:23:47.981
We're still going to that crash site.

1263
01:23:48.149 --> 01:23:49.816
What's at that crash site
that you want so badly?

1264
01:23:50.943 --> 01:23:52.652
Weapons! Enough to kill it.

1265
01:23:52.820 --> 01:23:54.112
Kong didn't kill Chapman.

1266
01:23:54.280 --> 01:23:55.947
But he did kill these men!

1267
01:23:56.240 --> 01:23:58.366
My men!

1268
01:23:58.534 --> 01:23:59.951
MARLOW: You can't kill Kong. Colonel.

1269
01:24:00.119 --> 01:24:01.494
Kong is god on this island.

1270
01:24:01.662 --> 01:24:04.206
He's the only thing keeping
them lizard things in the ground.

1271
01:24:04.373 --> 01:24:06.208
BROOKS: He's right. Colonel.
We can't kill Kong.

1272
01:24:06.375 --> 01:24:07.792
Now. that other creature?

1273
01:24:07.960 --> 01:24:10.462
That's the threat.
And there are more of them down there.

1274
01:24:10.630 --> 01:24:12.881
If you take away
a species' natural competition.

1275
01:24:13.049 --> 01:24:14.299
they'll proliferate out of control.

1276
01:24:14.467 --> 01:24:15.675
Then we'll end them. too!

1277
01:24:15.843 --> 01:24:17.886
After we bring this thing down.

1278
01:24:18.054 --> 01:24:19.471
I can't let you do that. Colonel.

1279
01:24:19.639 --> 01:24:20.680
CONRAD: Whoa. whoa.
Wait! Hold your fire!

1280
01:24:21.474 --> 01:24:22.933
- (GRUNTS)
- (GROANS)

1281
01:24:24.310 --> 01:24:26.561
This is one war we are not gonna lose.

1282
01:24:26.729 --> 01:24:27.854
MARLOW: Nuts!

1283
01:24:28.022 --> 01:24:30.023
You hear me? This is nuts!

1284
01:24:30.191 --> 01:24:31.816
Please! You need to listen to us!

1285
01:24:31.984 --> 01:24:33.318
We're not at war. Colonel.
You're making a mistake.

1286
01:24:33.486 --> 01:24:34.986
Your lies got my men killed!

1287
01:24:35.154 --> 01:24:37.072
- And you're gonna get us all killed!
- CONRAD: Not our fight.

1288
01:24:38.199 --> 01:24:40.158
Whose side are you on. Captain?

1289
01:24:40.326 --> 01:24:41.701
Okay. Colonel.

1290
01:24:42.495 --> 01:24:44.663
You'll find your Sea Stallion
three klicks up that ridge.

1291
01:24:45.915 --> 01:24:48.833
Now. I'm gonna take these civilians
back to the boat.

1292
01:24:49.001 --> 01:24:50.460
And we'll wait for you there.

1293
01:24:50.628 --> 01:24:52.003
All right?

1294
01:25:06.519 --> 01:25:07.519
Saddle up!

1295
01:25:09.063 --> 01:25:10.814
Let's go kill this thing!

1296
01:25:14.527 --> 01:25:16.945
- (SIGHS)
- Steve.

1297
01:25:17.113 --> 01:25:19.531
you running with the big dogs
or staying on the porch?

1298
01:25:20.449 --> 01:25:22.033
I don't wanna be on the porch.

1299
01:25:22.201 --> 01:25:23.451
CONRAD: Marlow. you okay?

1300
01:25:24.704 --> 01:25:26.246
We need to stop him.

1301
01:25:26.414 --> 01:25:27.664
You wanna talk with him about it again?

1302
01:25:27.832 --> 01:25:29.541
He seemed to really go for it
the first time.

1303
01:25:29.709 --> 01:25:31.042
He's losing his grip.

1304
01:25:32.712 --> 01:25:33.878
Now. follow me.

1305
01:25:34.714 --> 01:25:36.548
and we'll get off this rock alive.

1306
01:25:41.220 --> 01:25:42.220
CHAPMAN: Dear Billy...

1307
01:25:43.973 --> 01:25:46.308
I'm just trying to get home
to you and your mom.

1308
01:25:47.393 --> 01:25:48.893
You be strong. now.

1309
01:25:50.104 --> 01:25:51.479
Much love.

1310
01:25:58.446 --> 01:26:00.780
Make sure those get back to his family.

1311
01:26:01.991 --> 01:26:03.241
Dear Billy...

1312
01:26:05.661 --> 01:26:08.121
Your dad was one of the best
to ever do it.

1313
01:26:15.963 --> 01:26:17.422
CONRAD: There's water close by.

1314
01:26:17.923 --> 01:26:20.300
Are you lost? Which way?

1315
01:26:21.093 --> 01:26:22.260
CONRAD: Hang on.

1316
01:26:26.432 --> 01:26:28.058
(DISTANT ROARING)

1317
01:26:35.274 --> 01:26:36.358
Wait here.

1318
01:26:37.318 --> 01:26:39.527
I've got to get to higher ground
to find the river.

1319
01:26:41.655 --> 01:26:44.240
WEAVER: Hey! I'm coming. too.

1320
01:26:44.450 --> 01:26:45.992
- (GUN COCKS)
- I'll be right here.

1321
01:26:48.829 --> 01:26:50.455
Keep your eyes open.

1322
01:26:51.499 --> 01:26:52.874
Up in the trees. too.

1323
01:26:53.667 --> 01:26:54.667
Why?

1324
01:26:54.835 --> 01:26:55.960
Ants.

1325
01:26:56.962 --> 01:26:58.129
Big ones.

1326
01:26:59.131 --> 01:27:00.131
There's one.

1327
01:27:01.884 --> 01:27:04.052
Sounds like a bird.
but it's a fucking ant.

1328
01:27:12.645 --> 01:27:15.855
PACKARD: Gather up everything you can.
including those seismic charges.

1329
01:27:16.816 --> 01:27:18.983
They got his attention the first time.

1330
01:27:27.076 --> 01:27:28.076
(SIGHS)

1331
01:27:28.786 --> 01:27:30.328
(FLIES BUZZING)

1332
01:27:33.165 --> 01:27:34.874
This is a bad idea.

1333
01:27:35.042 --> 01:27:36.292
COLE: Let's just get on with it.

1334
01:27:36.836 --> 01:27:37.877
PACKARD: Mills. Cole.

1335
01:27:38.045 --> 01:27:39.295
let's prep this ordinance.

1336
01:27:40.047 --> 01:27:42.090
Make him a special gift
out of that napalm.

1337
01:28:00.734 --> 01:28:01.734
(WEAVER GRUNTING)

1338
01:28:13.539 --> 01:28:15.790
CONRAD: The boat must be around that bend.

1339
01:28:17.585 --> 01:28:18.585
(CAMERA CLICKS)

1340
01:28:32.391 --> 01:28:34.809
(BREATH TREMBLING)

1341
01:28:48.282 --> 01:28:49.574
(SNIFFING)

1342
01:29:33.619 --> 01:29:35.119
(CHUCKLING)

1343
01:29:46.131 --> 01:29:47.924
(PANTING)

1344
01:30:04.483 --> 01:30:06.150
(ROARING)

1345
01:30:08.153 --> 01:30:10.655
We have to go. Now.

1346
01:30:38.100 --> 01:30:39.100
- (DISTANT ROARING)
- (GASPS)

1347
01:30:39.310 --> 01:30:40.310
(GUNS COCK)

1348
01:30:41.562 --> 01:30:42.854
Don't shoot!

1349
01:30:43.230 --> 01:30:44.230
(GASPING)

1350
01:30:45.441 --> 01:30:47.108
Conrad. which way are we going?

1351
01:30:47.276 --> 01:30:50.236
You three need to go back to the boat.
It's that way.

1352
01:30:50.613 --> 01:30:52.071
Wait for us till dawn.

1353
01:30:52.239 --> 01:30:53.865
If we're not back by then.

1354
01:30:54.450 --> 01:30:55.533
just go.

1355
01:30:55.701 --> 01:30:56.951
(SCOFFS) You ain't gotta twist my arm.

1356
01:30:57.119 --> 01:30:58.786
Where are you two going?

1357
01:31:00.539 --> 01:31:02.123
We're going to save Kong.

1358
01:31:03.208 --> 01:31:04.792
Not without me. pal.

1359
01:31:10.007 --> 01:31:11.007
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

1360
01:31:35.407 --> 01:31:36.407
(ROARING)

1361
01:31:40.037 --> 01:31:41.037
(GASPS)

1362
01:31:54.385 --> 01:31:55.385
(ROARING IN PAIN)

1363
01:32:06.438 --> 01:32:07.438
(CONTINUES ROARING)

1364
01:32:34.550 --> 01:32:35.550
(ROARING)

1365
01:32:42.808 --> 01:32:43.808
(SCREAMING)

1366
01:32:45.185 --> 01:32:46.185
Oh. dear.

1367
01:32:46.812 --> 01:32:47.812
(SCREAMS)

1368
01:33:01.535 --> 01:33:02.535
(GROANS)

1369
01:33:10.586 --> 01:33:11.669
PACKARD: Men!

1370
01:33:11.837 --> 01:33:13.504
Place your charges.

1371
01:33:14.381 --> 01:33:16.174
It's time to show Kong

1372
01:33:16.341 --> 01:33:19.010
that man is king!

1373
01:33:20.053 --> 01:33:21.053
- (BEEPS)
- RELES: Arm one.

1374
01:33:21.472 --> 01:33:22.472
- (BEEPS)
- COLE: Arm two.

1375
01:33:23.098 --> 01:33:24.098
- (BEEPS)
- MILLS: Arm three.

1376
01:33:26.727 --> 01:33:27.727
Packard!

1377
01:33:34.193 --> 01:33:35.526
Don't do it.

1378
01:33:39.698 --> 01:33:42.241
I asked you fellas nice the first time.

1379
01:33:42.409 --> 01:33:43.785
CONRAD: We don't wanna
fight here. Packard.

1380
01:33:43.952 --> 01:33:46.037
This thing brought us down!
It killed my men!

1381
01:33:46.205 --> 01:33:47.872
Kong was just defending his territory.

1382
01:33:48.040 --> 01:33:49.791
We are soldiers!

1383
01:33:49.958 --> 01:33:51.250
We do the dirty work.

1384
01:33:51.418 --> 01:33:54.462
so our families and our countrymen
don't have to be afraid!

1385
01:33:54.630 --> 01:33:57.381
They shouldn't even know
a thing like this exists!

1386
01:33:58.258 --> 01:33:59.717
You've lost your mind.

1387
01:34:02.221 --> 01:34:04.138
Put that detonator down.

1388
01:34:13.899 --> 01:34:15.358
(BEEPING)

1389
01:34:17.528 --> 01:34:18.528
WEAVER: Stop!

1390
01:34:22.741 --> 01:34:24.909
The world is bigger than this.

1391
01:34:25.494 --> 01:34:26.994
Bitch. please!

1392
01:34:27.162 --> 01:34:29.789
Slivko. get her out of there!

1393
01:34:31.792 --> 01:34:34.544
You know it's the wrong thing to do. son.

1394
01:34:35.254 --> 01:34:36.254
(SNIFFLES)

1395
01:34:51.436 --> 01:34:52.603
Put it down. sir.

1396
01:34:53.188 --> 01:34:54.438
CONRAD: Packard!

1397
01:35:08.120 --> 01:35:09.120
Come on.

1398
01:35:09.997 --> 01:35:10.997
It's over.

1399
01:35:11.498 --> 01:35:12.498
(WATER BUBBLING)

1400
01:35:27.222 --> 01:35:28.389
That's the big one.

1401
01:35:28.682 --> 01:35:29.682
Fall back.

1402
01:35:30.809 --> 01:35:31.809
(SNARLING)

1403
01:35:33.353 --> 01:35:34.353
Go!

1404
01:35:39.318 --> 01:35:40.318
(SCREECHING)

1405
01:35:44.323 --> 01:35:45.323
Colonel.

1406
01:35:46.617 --> 01:35:47.617
Sir!

1407
01:35:50.120 --> 01:35:51.329
(CONTINUES SCREECHING)

1408
01:36:03.467 --> 01:36:04.717
(DETONATOR BEEPING)

1409
01:36:09.264 --> 01:36:10.514
Die. you mother...

1410
01:36:15.854 --> 01:36:16.854
(SCREECHING)

1411
01:36:18.148 --> 01:36:19.148
(ROARING)

1412
01:36:28.200 --> 01:36:29.867
- (WEAVER YELPS)
- Kong's down. Let's go!

1413
01:36:35.791 --> 01:36:37.124
They told us to leave at dawn.

1414
01:36:37.292 --> 01:36:38.292
- I know.
- SAN: It's dawn.

1415
01:36:38.460 --> 01:36:39.543
I know!

1416
01:36:39.711 --> 01:36:40.878
So what are we going to do?

1417
01:36:41.380 --> 01:36:42.380
(PANTING)

1418
01:36:49.554 --> 01:36:51.222
(ALL PANTING)

1419
01:36:54.559 --> 01:36:56.102
CONRAD: This is the edge of the island.

1420
01:36:56.895 --> 01:37:00.147
Weaver. get up on those rocks
and fire a flare.

1421
01:37:00.315 --> 01:37:02.066
- With any luck. Brooks will see it.
- (RUSTLING)

1422
01:37:04.903 --> 01:37:06.237
We'll buy you time.

1423
01:37:08.657 --> 01:37:09.907
This way.

1424
01:37:12.995 --> 01:37:14.203
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

1425
01:37:15.080 --> 01:37:16.080
(SNARLING)

1426
01:37:18.500 --> 01:37:19.667
(SCREECHING)

1427
01:37:24.339 --> 01:37:26.799
CONRAD: Come on. Every second counts.

1428
01:37:33.807 --> 01:37:34.807
MILLS: Cole!

1429
01:37:35.308 --> 01:37:37.059
Come on. man. we gotta fall back.

1430
01:37:37.894 --> 01:37:39.228
Go live your life.

1431
01:37:39.604 --> 01:37:40.938
Get out of here.

1432
01:37:43.775 --> 01:37:44.775
- Cole. no!
- Cole!

1433
01:37:44.943 --> 01:37:46.027
- Cole. no!
- Stop!

1434
01:37:46.194 --> 01:37:48.696
RELES: Cole!
MILLS: Cole! Cole!

1435
01:37:49.114 --> 01:37:51.073
No! Don't!

1436
01:37:51.616 --> 01:37:53.659
ALL: Cole!

1437
01:37:53.827 --> 01:37:54.910
Cole!

1438
01:37:55.787 --> 01:37:57.413
(ALL SHOUTING)

1439
01:38:01.126 --> 01:38:04.295
Come on. Come on. you son of a bitch.

1440
01:38:04.504 --> 01:38:06.047
(SCREECHING)

1441
01:38:16.308 --> 01:38:17.308
(PANTING)

1442
01:38:20.812 --> 01:38:21.812
(SCREECHES)

1443
01:38:22.856 --> 01:38:24.106
(ALL PANTING)

1444
01:38:27.152 --> 01:38:28.152
(SCREECHING)

1445
01:38:28.487 --> 01:38:29.487
(ROARING)

1446
01:38:30.155 --> 01:38:31.655
Come on! Go!

1447
01:38:32.282 --> 01:38:33.657
(ALL CONTINUE PANTING)

1448
01:38:50.300 --> 01:38:51.300
(ROARING)

1449
01:39:09.194 --> 01:39:10.194
(PANTING)

1450
01:39:24.209 --> 01:39:25.209
(ROARING)

1451
01:39:27.337 --> 01:39:28.337
(SNARLING)

1452
01:39:33.760 --> 01:39:34.760
(ROARING)

1453
01:39:35.387 --> 01:39:36.387
(SCREECHING)

1454
01:40:19.097 --> 01:40:20.681
Come on! Go!

1455
01:40:23.351 --> 01:40:24.935
SAN: Come on! Hurry!

1456
01:40:29.566 --> 01:40:30.566
(GROANS)

1457
01:40:31.109 --> 01:40:32.610
MARLOW: (PANTING) Come on!

1458
01:40:34.571 --> 01:40:35.738
(BROOKS PANTING)

1459
01:40:40.118 --> 01:40:41.118
Marlow. a little help here!

1460
01:40:41.286 --> 01:40:42.661
I got it. She's temperamental. Watch out!

1461
01:40:46.875 --> 01:40:47.875
(KONG GRUNTING)

1462
01:40:54.132 --> 01:40:55.132
(ROARING)

1463
01:40:56.927 --> 01:40:57.927
(SCREECHING)

1464
01:40:59.429 --> 01:41:00.429
(GRUNTING)

1465
01:41:08.605 --> 01:41:09.605
(ROARING)

1466
01:41:20.992 --> 01:41:22.451
(COCKS)

1467
01:41:27.165 --> 01:41:28.332
(SCREECHING)

1468
01:41:32.712 --> 01:41:34.463
- MARLOW: Clear!
- Clear!

1469
01:41:35.048 --> 01:41:36.131
(GUN FIRING)

1470
01:41:36.800 --> 01:41:38.175
Come on. you bastard!

1471
01:41:40.345 --> 01:41:41.845
(SCREECHING)

1472
01:41:48.186 --> 01:41:49.812
(ROARING)

1473
01:41:51.523 --> 01:41:52.523
(SHRIEKS)

1474
01:41:53.441 --> 01:41:54.608
(SCREECHING)

1475
01:42:23.096 --> 01:42:24.555
(SCREAMS)

1476
01:42:29.436 --> 01:42:30.477
Weaver!

1477
01:42:34.232 --> 01:42:35.232
(SCREECHING)

1478
01:42:57.464 --> 01:42:58.756
(SCREECHES)

1479
01:43:20.278 --> 01:43:21.278
(GROANS)

1480
01:43:42.801 --> 01:43:44.009
(ROARING)

1481
01:44:18.670 --> 01:44:20.504
Weaver? Weaver.

1482
01:44:20.797 --> 01:44:22.423
Hey. hey. hey. Hey.

1483
01:44:22.757 --> 01:44:23.757
(COUGHING)

1484
01:44:26.177 --> 01:44:27.219
You're okay.

1485
01:44:55.457 --> 01:44:57.040
(WEAVER BREATHING SHAKILY)

1486
01:45:18.563 --> 01:45:20.397
So what do you think. fellas?

1487
01:45:20.565 --> 01:45:22.232
This way to Key West?

1488
01:45:23.234 --> 01:45:24.651
I think it is. brother.

1489
01:45:26.154 --> 01:45:27.571
CONRAD: This place will change.

1490
01:45:28.740 --> 01:45:30.157
Word will get out.

1491
01:45:30.950 --> 01:45:32.075
It always does.

1492
01:45:32.911 --> 01:45:35.078
Well. it's not coming from us.

1493
01:45:39.667 --> 01:45:43.420
(SINGING)
We'll meet again

1494
01:45:44.506 --> 01:45:46.757
Don't know where

1495
01:45:46.925 --> 01:45:49.927
Don't know when

1496
01:45:50.094 --> 01:45:53.472
But I know we'll meet again

1497
01:45:54.349 --> 01:45:56.642
- (SONG CONTINUES PLAYING)
- (CAMERA CLICKS)

1498
01:46:26.589 --> 01:46:27.798
(BIRDS CAWING)

1499
01:46:49.070 --> 01:46:50.737
(ROARS)

1500
01:47:06.254 --> 01:47:07.296
(PROJECTOR WHIRRING)

1501
01:48:21.954 --> 01:48:23.163
MALE SPORTS COMMENTATOR:
Ladies and gentlemen.

1502
01:48:23.373 --> 01:48:25.165
here we go now
to the Cub half of number eight.

1503
01:48:25.333 --> 01:48:26.917
If you want to see a crowd go crazy.

1504
01:48:27.085 --> 01:48:29.836
see what happens
if this guy hits one right now.

1505
01:48:30.922 --> 01:48:32.756
- Fly ball. very deep.
- (CROWD CHEERING)

1506
01:48:34.926 --> 01:48:35.926
(COMMENTATORS WHOOPING)

1507
01:48:36.511 --> 01:48:38.428
MALE SPORTS COMMENTATOR:
And the impossible dream

1508
01:48:38.638 --> 01:48:40.847
just became the possible dream!

1509
01:56:43.998 --> 01:56:45.498
CONRAD: You just gonna sit there?

1510
01:56:48.085 --> 01:56:49.335
In the dark.

1511
01:56:50.504 --> 01:56:52.505
You're enjoying this. right?

1512
01:56:53.632 --> 01:56:55.592
Is this fun for you?

1513
01:56:55.759 --> 01:56:57.927
I promise I won't tell the Russians.

1514
01:56:58.095 --> 01:57:00.096
- I promise I will tell the Russians.
- She's gonna tell the Russians.

1515
01:57:08.355 --> 01:57:09.939
Why are you keeping us here?

1516
01:57:10.107 --> 01:57:11.941
- I wanna go home.
- We get it.

1517
01:57:12.109 --> 01:57:13.443
There was no island.

1518
01:57:13.611 --> 01:57:14.986
- We were never on an island.
- (DOOR OPENS)

1519
01:57:15.154 --> 01:57:16.154
BROOKS: Island?

1520
01:57:16.322 --> 01:57:17.447
What island?

1521
01:57:17.615 --> 01:57:19.240
Brooks. what the hell is going on?

1522
01:57:19.617 --> 01:57:20.992
Welcome to Monarch.

1523
01:57:21.410 --> 01:57:22.410
(CHUCKLING)

1524
01:57:23.787 --> 01:57:26.206
This island is just the beginning.

1525
01:57:26.373 --> 01:57:27.790
There's more out there.

1526
01:57:27.958 --> 01:57:29.500
What do you mean. "more"?

1527
01:57:29.668 --> 01:57:32.629
This world never belonged to us.
It belonged to them.

1528
01:57:32.796 --> 01:57:35.632
The question is
how long before they take it back.

1529
01:57:37.509 --> 01:57:40.595
Kong is not the only king.

1530
01:58:06.163 --> 01:58:07.997
(CREATURE ROARING)

1531
01:58:20.427 --> 01:58:21.427
English - SDH

1532
01:58:22.305 --> 01:59:22.398
